{"type":"message","id":"e17ffb41","parentId":"74e8278b","timestamp":"2026-04-03T02:00:59.821Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"tooluse_iebW5SMeuN85Lai1LiToVp","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# RobustMLLM-Diag: Adaptive Cross-Modal Imputation and Fusion in Multimodal Large Language Models for Noisy Fault Diagnosis\n\n## Abstract (~190 words total)\n- Industrial fault diagnosis challenge: Noisy multimodal data (vibration, images, spectra) with 20-50% modality missing/ noise.\n- Existing MLLM limitations: Rigid fusion ignores uncertainty/missing data.\n- Proposed RobustMLLM-Diag: Adaptive cross-modal imputation via RAG + uncertainty-aware attention fusion.\n- Key innovations: Bayesian dropout uncertainty, dynamic modality weighting, RL-optimized robustness.\n- Experiments: Superior accuracy (e.g., +15% under noise) on enhanced industrial datasets.\n- Contributions summary.\n\n## I. INTRODUCTION (~900 words total)\n- P1: Industrial rotating machinery importance, fault diagnosis evolution (~150 words) [Citations: 5]\n- P2: Multimodal data in diagnosis (vibration, thermal, acoustic); noise/missing challenges (~150 words) [Citations: 6]\n- P3: MLLM advances (e.g., LLaVA, Qwen-VL) but limitations in noisy industrial settings (~150 words) [Citations: 5]\n- P4: Gaps: Lack of adaptive imputation/fusion; prior arts (GANs, SMOTE for imbalance, but not multimodal noise) (~150 words) [Citations: 4]\n- Contributions (~150 words):\n  1. Adaptive cross-modal RAG imputation for missing modalities.\n  2. Uncertainty-aware attention for noisy fusion.\n  3. End-to-end + RL training for robustness.\n  4. Validation on 20-50% noise/missing industrial data.\n- Paper organization (~50 words).\n\n**Citations: 20 (≥50% total)**  \n**Figures: None**  \n**Tables: None**  \n**Equations: None**\n\n## II. THEORETICAL BACKGROUND (~1150 words total)\n### A. Multimodal Large Language Models (~300 words)\n- Vision-language pretraining (CLIP, Flamingo).\n- Cross-modal attention mechanisms.\n\n### B. Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) (~250 words)\n- Cross-modal retrieval for imputation.\n\n### C. Uncertainty Estimation in Noisy Data (~300 words)\n- Bayesian dropout for epistemic uncertainty.\n- Attention weighting.\n\n### D. Reinforcement Learning for Robustness (~300 words)\n- Policy optimization under simulated noise.\n\n**Citations: 8**  \n**Figures:**  \n- Fig. 1: MLLM architecture overview (conceptual diagram, full-page).  \n- Fig. 2: RAG pipeline (flowchart).  \n**Tables:** Table I: Notation summary.  \n**Equations (3):**  \n- (1) Cross-modal attention: \\( QK^T / \\sqrt{d} \\).  \n- (2) Bayesian dropout variance.  \n- (3) Wasserstein distance for RAG.\n\n## III. PROPOSED METHOD (~1650 words total)\n### A. Overall Framework (~300 words) [Fig. 3: Framework (figure*, double-column)]\n### B. Modality-Specific Encoders with Uncertainty (~400 words) [Eq. (4-6)]\n### C. Adaptive Cross-Modal Imputation (RAG) (~400 words) [Fig. 4: Imputation process]\n### D. Uncertainty-Aware Fusion (~400 words) [Eq. (7-9)]\n### E. Training: End-to-End + RL (~150 words) [Eq. (10-12)]\n\n**Citations: 3**  \n**Figures:** Fig. 3 (framework), Fig. 4 (RAG), Fig. 5 (attention weights visualization).  \n**Tables:** Table II: Hyperparameters.  \n**Equations (5):** (4) Encoder: \\( h_i = E_i(x_i) \\); (5) Uncertainty: \\( u_i = Var(MC Dropout) \\); (6-12) Fusion/RL losses.\n\n## IV. EXPERIMENTS (~2650 words total)\n### A. Datasets and Setup (~400 words) [Table III: Datasets stats]\n### B. Baselines and Metrics (~200 words)\n### C. Main Results (~600 words) [Table IV: Accuracy comparison; Fig. 6-8: Noise/missing ablation]\n### D. Ablation Studies (~500 words) [Table V: Component ablation; Fig. 9: Uncertainty viz]\n### E. Qualitative Analysis (~400 words) [Fig. 10: Attention maps; Table VI: Failure cases]\n### F. Efficiency (~300 words) [Table VII: Runtime/FLOPs; Fig. 11: Scalability]\n### G. Real-World Deployment (~250 words) [Table VIII: Industrial test]\n\n**Citations: 3**  \n**Figures (6):** Fig. 6 (acc vs noise), Fig. 7 (missing modality), Fig. 8 (confusion matrices), Fig. 9 (t-SNE), Fig. 10 (attention), Fig. 11 (scalability).  \n**Tables (5):** III (datasets), IV (results), V (ablation), VI (qual), VII (eff), VIII (real-world).  \n**Equations (4):** Metrics like F1, robustness loss.\n\n## V. CONCLUSION (~190 words total)\n- Summary of contributions and results.\n- Limitations and future work.\n\n**Citations: 1**  \n**Figures/Tables/Equations: None**\n\n**Total Word Count Verification:** 190+900+1150+1650+2650+190=6730 (adjustable to ~7200 with details).  \n**Total Figures: 11**  \n**Total Tables: 8**  \n**Total Equations: 12**  \n**Total Citations: 35**\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775181659820}}
