{"type":"message","id":"37fe010f","parentId":"2b8be7a7","timestamp":"2026-04-03T02:46:44.621Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"v2 is at 6323w total (88% of 7200 target). Intro at 791w is a bit low (target 800-1000). The v3 directory has polish outputs from a parallel session that jumped ahead. I need to:\n\n1. Consolidate v2 — Intro needs ~100 more words\n2. Stop the premature v3 polish tasks\n3. Run 4.5 R2 review on v2 before proceeding\n\nThe Intro drop from 953→791 was caused by a late Writer task overwriting. Let me fix Intro and then submit for review."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tooluse_IpzQ791loH6GwpWAMgcZZz","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Intro is 791w, needs to be ~900. Let me check what happened\nhead -5 /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v2/introduction.tex\necho \"...\"\ntail -10 /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v2/introduction.tex","timeout":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"claude-proxy","model":"claude-opus-4-6","usage":{"input":94151,"output":255,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":94406,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775184392963}}
{"type":"message","id":"08de4065","parentId":"37fe010f","timestamp":"2026-04-03T02:46:44.628Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"tooluse_IpzQ791loH6GwpWAMgcZZz","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\\section{Introduction}\n\nRotating machinery, such as bearings, gears, and motors, forms the backbone of modern industrial systems, including power generation, manufacturing, aviation, and petrochemical processes \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. These components are subjected to harsh operating conditions, including high speeds, variable loads, and environmental stressors, leading to inevitable faults like wear, cracks, and imbalances. Undetected faults can escalate into catastrophic failures, resulting in substantial economic losses estimated at billions annually, unplanned downtime, and safety hazards \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Notable incidents underscore this vulnerability: the 2009 gearbox failures at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm affected 80 turbines due to progressive gear wear, causing over 10\\% capacity loss; the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 incident involved an uncontained Rolls-Royce Trent 900 engine failure traced to bearing damage; and the 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 fan blade failure originated from bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}. Traditional fault diagnosis relied on physical models and signal processing techniques, such as Fourier transforms and wavelet analysis. Deep learning revolutionized the field with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit}, achieving superior accuracy on benchmark datasets like CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing} by learning hierarchical representations directly from raw signals \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these advances, single-modality methods struggle with complex fault patterns under varying conditions, underscoring the need for integrated multimodal strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n\nMultimodal data fusion has emerged as a promising paradigm for enhancing fault diagnosis robustness by leveraging complementary information from diverse sensors. Vibration signals captured via accelerometers provide temporal dynamics of mechanical faults; thermal imaging reveals heat anomalies from friction or misalignment; acoustic emissions detect early-stage cracks through high-frequency sounds \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Studies have demonstrated that fusing these modalities via attention mechanisms or graph neural networks improves diagnostic accuracy by 5--10\\% over unimodal baselines, particularly under variable speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. However, industrial deployments face significant challenges: sensor noise from electromagnetic interference and environmental factors corrupts data; partial occlusions or sensor failures lead to missing modalities in up to 50\\% of real-world scenarios. Conventional fusion techniques, such as early or late fusion, assume complete data availability and falter under noise, amplifying errors in cross-modal alignment \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n...\n\nMultimodal data fusion has emerged as a promising paradigm for enhancing fault diagnosis robustness by leveraging complementary information from diverse sensors. Vibration signals captured via accelerometers provide temporal dynamics of mechanical faults; thermal imaging reveals heat anomalies from friction or misalignment; acoustic emissions detect early-stage cracks through high-frequency sounds \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Studies have demonstrated that fusing these modalities via attention mechanisms or graph neural networks improves diagnostic accuracy by 5--10\\% over unimodal baselines, particularly under variable speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. However, industrial deployments face significant challenges: sensor noise from electromagnetic interference and environmental factors corrupts data; partial occlusions or sensor failures lead to missing modalities in up to 50\\% of real-world scenarios. Conventional fusion techniques, such as early or late fusion, assume complete data availability and falter under noise, amplifying errors in cross-modal alignment \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n\nMultimodal large language models (MLLMs) represent the latest frontier, integrating vision-language pretraining to reason over images, spectrograms, and text descriptions. Models like LLaVA \\cite{liu2023llava,lu2024}, BLIP-2 \\cite{blip2}, Flamingo \\cite{flamingo}, and Qwen-VL \\cite{qwen} achieve remarkable zero-shot capabilities on natural images but struggle in industrial contexts. Noisy spectrograms from vibration data introduce artifacts that mislead visual encoders; unstructured thermal images lack semantic priors, causing hallucinations in fault localization. Evaluations on PHM datasets reveal 15--20\\% accuracy drops in noisy environments compared to clean benchmarks, with LLaVA's bearing fault classification accuracy dropping from 92\\% to 74\\% under 20~dB SNR and Qwen-VL's thermal anomaly detection degrading from 88\\% to 70\\% in dusty conditions \\cite{hoang2025,kim2024,lu2024}.\n\nA critical research gap persists in handling missing or noisy multimodal data within MLLMs for industrial fault diagnosis. Existing generative methods, such as GANs \\cite{arjovsky2017wgan,wu2023} and SMOTE variants, effectively mitigate class imbalance but fail to address cross-modal inconsistencies or missing modalities, often producing misaligned features that degrade downstream fusion \\cite{wu2023,guo2023}. Traditional imputation strategies like mean-filling or linear interpolation disregard temporal-spatial correlations inherent in multimodal signals, leading to suboptimal reconstructions under variable operating conditions \\cite{guo2023}. Key limitations of prior approaches include: (1) lack of cross-modal consistency in synthetic data generation; (2) ignorance of modality-specific noise characteristics; (3) absence of uncertainty estimation in fusion layers; (4) no integration of external knowledge retrieval for imputation; and (5) insufficient end-to-end optimization under realistic noise distributions \\cite{wu2023,guo2023,gal2016dropout}. Moreover, standard attention layers in current MLLMs propagate noise without weighting reliability, while retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), successful in NLP tasks \\cite{lewis2020rag}, has not been adapted for multimodal imputation in fault diagnosis. These limitations result in 20--50\\% performance degradation on real-world industrial datasets with noise and missing modalities.\n\nThe contributions of this work are fourfold. First, we propose an adaptive cross-modal RAG imputation module that retrieves similar historical clean multimodal samples from a vector database and reconstructs missing or noisy modalities through specialized vision-language prompts, ensuring temporal and semantic alignment across vibration spectrograms, thermal images, and acoustic waveforms. Second, we introduce an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism employing evidential deep learning to dynamically weight modal reliabilities, mitigating error propagation during fusion and enhancing decision confidence under partial observations. Third, we develop an end-to-end training paradigm augmented with reinforcement learning, where diagnostic policies are optimized via rewards reflecting accuracy and robustness against simulated industrial perturbations like 20--50\\% noise injection. Fourth, we conduct comprehensive validation on benchmark datasets (CWRU, Paderborn) and real industrial datasets with emulated missing rates up to 50\\%, demonstrating state-of-the-art accuracy improvements of 12--18\\% over baselines while maintaining robustness.\n\nThe remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section~\\ref{sec:background} reviews related work. Section~\\ref{sec:method} details the proposed RobustMLLM-Diag framework. Section~\\ref{sec:experiments} presents experiments and results. Section~\\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes with future directions."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":4,"aggregated":"\\section{Introduction}\n\nRotating machinery, such as bearings, gears, and motors, forms the backbone of modern industrial systems, including power generation, manufacturing, aviation, and petrochemical processes \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. These components are subjected to harsh operating conditions, including high speeds, variable loads, and environmental stressors, leading to inevitable faults like wear, cracks, and imbalances. Undetected faults can escalate into catastrophic failures, resulting in substantial economic losses estimated at billions annually, unplanned downtime, and safety hazards \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Notable incidents underscore this vulnerability: the 2009 gearbox failures at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm affected 80 turbines due to progressive gear wear, causing over 10\\% capacity loss; the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 incident involved an uncontained Rolls-Royce Trent 900 engine failure traced to bearing damage; and the 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 fan blade failure originated from bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}. Traditional fault diagnosis relied on physical models and signal processing techniques, such as Fourier transforms and wavelet analysis. Deep learning revolutionized the field with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit}, achieving superior accuracy on benchmark datasets like CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing} by learning hierarchical representations directly from raw signals \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these advances, single-modality methods struggle with complex fault patterns under varying conditions, underscoring the need for integrated multimodal strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n\nMultimodal data fusion has emerged as a promising paradigm for enhancing fault diagnosis robustness by leveraging complementary information from diverse sensors. Vibration signals captured via accelerometers provide temporal dynamics of mechanical faults; thermal imaging reveals heat anomalies from friction or misalignment; acoustic emissions detect early-stage cracks through high-frequency sounds \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Studies have demonstrated that fusing these modalities via attention mechanisms or graph neural networks improves diagnostic accuracy by 5--10\\% over unimodal baselines, particularly under variable speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. However, industrial deployments face significant challenges: sensor noise from electromagnetic interference and environmental factors corrupts data; partial occlusions or sensor failures lead to missing modalities in up to 50\\% of real-world scenarios. Conventional fusion techniques, such as early or late fusion, assume complete data availability and falter under noise, amplifying errors in cross-modal alignment \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n...\n\nMultimodal data fusion has emerged as a promising paradigm for enhancing fault diagnosis robustness by leveraging complementary information from diverse sensors. Vibration signals captured via accelerometers provide temporal dynamics of mechanical faults; thermal imaging reveals heat anomalies from friction or misalignment; acoustic emissions detect early-stage cracks through high-frequency sounds \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Studies have demonstrated that fusing these modalities via attention mechanisms or graph neural networks improves diagnostic accuracy by 5--10\\% over unimodal baselines, particularly under variable speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. However, industrial deployments face significant challenges: sensor noise from electromagnetic interference and environmental factors corrupts data; partial occlusions or sensor failures lead to missing modalities in up to 50\\% of real-world scenarios. Conventional fusion techniques, such as early or late fusion, assume complete data availability and falter under noise, amplifying errors in cross-modal alignment \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n\nMultimodal large language models (MLLMs) represent the latest frontier, integrating vision-language pretraining to reason over images, spectrograms, and text descriptions. Models like LLaVA \\cite{liu2023llava,lu2024}, BLIP-2 \\cite{blip2}, Flamingo \\cite{flamingo}, and Qwen-VL \\cite{qwen} achieve remarkable zero-shot capabilities on natural images but struggle in industrial contexts. Noisy spectrograms from vibration data introduce artifacts that mislead visual encoders; unstructured thermal images lack semantic priors, causing hallucinations in fault localization. Evaluations on PHM datasets reveal 15--20\\% accuracy drops in noisy environments compared to clean benchmarks, with LLaVA's bearing fault classification accuracy dropping from 92\\% to 74\\% under 20~dB SNR and Qwen-VL's thermal anomaly detection degrading from 88\\% to 70\\% in dusty conditions \\cite{hoang2025,kim2024,lu2024}.\n\nA critical research gap persists in handling missing or noisy multimodal data within MLLMs for industrial fault diagnosis. Existing generative methods, such as GANs \\cite{arjovsky2017wgan,wu2023} and SMOTE variants, effectively mitigate class imbalance but fail to address cross-modal inconsistencies or missing modalities, often producing misaligned features that degrade downstream fusion \\cite{wu2023,guo2023}. Traditional imputation strategies like mean-filling or linear interpolation disregard temporal-spatial correlations inherent in multimodal signals, leading to suboptimal reconstructions under variable operating conditions \\cite{guo2023}. Key limitations of prior approaches include: (1) lack of cross-modal consistency in synthetic data generation; (2) ignorance of modality-specific noise characteristics; (3) absence of uncertainty estimation in fusion layers; (4) no integration of external knowledge retrieval for imputation; and (5) insufficient end-to-end optimization under realistic noise distributions \\cite{wu2023,guo2023,gal2016dropout}. Moreover, standard attention layers in current MLLMs propagate noise without weighting reliability, while retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), successful in NLP tasks \\cite{lewis2020rag}, has not been adapted for multimodal imputation in fault diagnosis. These limitations result in 20--50\\% performance degradation on real-world industrial datasets with noise and missing modalities.\n\nThe contributions of this work are fourfold. First, we propose an adaptive cross-modal RAG imputation module that retrieves similar historical clean multimodal samples from a vector database and reconstructs missing or noisy modalities through specialized vision-language prompts, ensuring temporal and semantic alignment across vibration spectrograms, thermal images, and acoustic waveforms. Second, we introduce an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism employing evidential deep learning to dynamically weight modal reliabilities, mitigating error propagation during fusion and enhancing decision confidence under partial observations. Third, we develop an end-to-end training paradigm augmented with reinforcement learning, where diagnostic policies are optimized via rewards reflecting accuracy and robustness against simulated industrial perturbations like 20--50\\% noise injection. Fourth, we conduct comprehensive validation on benchmark datasets (CWRU, Paderborn) and real industrial datasets with emulated missing rates up to 50\\%, demonstrating state-of-the-art accuracy improvements of 12--18\\% over baselines while maintaining robustness.\n\nThe remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section~\\ref{sec:background} reviews related work. Section~\\ref{sec:method} details the proposed RobustMLLM-Diag framework. Section~\\ref{sec:experiments} presents experiments and results. Section~\\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes with future directions.","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775184404626}}
