{"type":"message","id":"4a92ea65","parentId":"442f26dc","timestamp":"2026-04-03T02:56:23.058Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"tooluse_l5ORTQN9uL2pZN3E6APvjn","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\\section{Proposed Method}\n\\label{sec:method}\n\nThis section presents the RobustMLLM-Diag framework, which addresses the limitations of existing MLLMs in noisy and incomplete multimodal fault diagnosis. Building upon the theoretical foundations in Section~\\ref{sec:background}, our approach integrates modality-specific encoders with uncertainty estimation, adaptive cross-modal imputation via RAG, uncertainty-aware fusion, and reinforcement learning (RL) for end-to-end robustness training.\n\n\\subsection{A. Overall Framework}\n\\label{subsec:framework}\n\nFig.~\\ref{fig:framework} illustrates the overall architecture of RobustMLLM-Diag. The framework processes three industrial modalities---vibration signals $x_v \\in \\mathbb{R}^{T \\times 1}$, thermal images $x_t \\in \\mathbb{R}^{H \\times W \\times 3}$, and acoustic emissions $x_a \\in \\mathbb{R}^{T \\times F}$---commonly encountered in rotating machinery diagnostics.\n\nThe pipeline begins with modality-specific encoders $E_i(\\cdot)$, $i \\in \\{v,t,a\\}$, which extract latent representations $h_i = E_i(x_i)$ augmented with epistemic uncertainty estimates $u_i$ via Bayesian Monte Carlo (MC) dropout \\cite{gal2016dropout}. For missing or severely noisy modalities, a retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) module imputes synthetic samples $\\hat{x}_i$ by querying a corpus of clean historical data using cross-modal dense retrieval (e.g., CLIP embeddings \\cite{clip}), conditioned on available modalities and diagnostic prompts. The imputed $\\hat{x}_i$ is then encoded to $\\hat{h}_i$ with corresponding $\\hat{u}_i$.\n\nThese representations are fused via an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism, which dynamically weights modalities based on reliability: $h_f = \\sum_i \\alpha_i h_i$, where $\\alpha_i = \\text{softmax}(-u_i / \\tau)$ and $\\tau$ is a temperature parameter. The fused embedding $h_f$ is projected into the LLM's input space and processed through cross-modal attention layers (Eq.~\\eqref{eq:attention}) for fault reasoning, yielding predictions $\\hat{y}$.\n\nAs detailed in Fig.~\\ref{fig:3}, the data flow is structured to ensure robustness and interpretability. Raw inputs first undergo preprocessing tailored to each modality: vibration signals are bandpass-filtered (0.1--10 kHz) and z-normalized; thermal images receive CLAHE enhancement and resizing to $224\\times224$; acoustic signals are windowed (1024-pt STFT, 50\\% overlap) into Mel-spectrograms. Encoded features $h_i$ and uncertainties $u_i$ from MC dropout ($T=50$) feed into conditional RAG logic—if $u_i > 0.5$, a query embedding $e_q = [e_{\\min u}; \\phi(p)]$ is formed from the least uncertain modality and prompt, retrieved via FAISS against pre-embedded corpus ($\\approx10^5$ samples), selecting top-k=5 for re-ranking and top-3 conditioning. Imputed samples follow the encoding path. Fusion applies uncertainty softmax weights, followed by multi-head cross-attention (8 heads, $d_k=96$) between vibration (query) and thermo-acoustic (KV) pairs. $h_f$ is projected (MLP, 768-dim) and tokenized for LLM prompt prefixing: ``Based on multimodal evidence [VISUAL TOKENS], diagnose the fault.'' This flow supports edge deployment with partial modality support and provides uncertainty visualizations for human-in-loop validation.\n\nTo enhance robustness, the entire framework is trained end-to-end under simulated noise (Gaussian, dropout, modality missing at 20-50\\%) using a composite loss $\\mathcal{L} = \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{CE}} + \\lambda_1 \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{RAG}} + \\lambda_2 \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{RL}}$, where $\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{RL}}$ employs PPO \\cite{schulman2017ppo} to optimize a policy $\\pi_\\theta$ maximizing diagnostic accuracy minus uncertainty penalties. This adaptive pipeline achieves superior performance on noisy PHM datasets, outperforming baselines by 15-20\\% under adverse conditions \\cite{lu2024,hoang2025}.\n\n\\subsection{B. Modality-Specific Encoders with Uncertainty}\n\\label{subsec:encoders}\n\nRobustMLLM-Diag employs tailored encoders for each modality to capture domain-specific fault signatures while quantifying prediction uncertainty.\n\nFor vibration signals, a 1D Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) processes raw time-series data: stacked Conv1D-ResNet blocks with kernel sizes 3-7 extract temporal harmonics indicative of bearing faults, followed by global average pooling to yield $h_v \\in \\mathbb{R}^{D}$. Thermal images are encoded using a Vision Transformer (ViT-B/16) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit}, dividing $224\\times224$ RGB frames into patches and applying self-attention to detect overheating patterns. Acoustic emissions are first converted to Mel-spectrograms ($S_a \\in \\mathbb{R}^{T/\\delta \\times M}$) via short-time Fourier transform (STFT) with 1024-point windows, then processed by a 2D CNN (ResNet-18 backbone) to capture frequency-domain impulsivity \\cite{liu2023}.\n\nFormally, the encoder for modality $i$ is defined as:\n\\begin{equation}\nh_i = E_i(x_i; \\theta_i),\n\\label{eq:encoder}\n\\end{equation}\nwhere $\\theta_i$ are modality-specific parameters.\n\nUncertainty estimation leverages Bayesian MC dropout \\cite{gal2016dropout}, retaining dropout during inference for $T=50$ stochastic forward passes: $h_i^{(t)} = E_i(x_i; \\theta_i, \\omega^{(t)})$, $\\omega^{(t)} \\sim \\text{Dropout}(p=0.1)$. The predictive mean is $\\bar{h}_i = \\frac{1}{T} \\sum_t h_i^{(t)}$, with epistemic uncertainty:\n\\begin{equation}\nu_i = \\text{Var}(\\{h_i^{(t)}\\}_{t=1}^T) = \\frac{1}{T} \\sum_t \\|h_i^{(t)} - \\bar{h}_i\\|^2.\n\\label{eq:uncertainty}\n\\end{equation}\nHigh $u_i$ indicates unreliable inputs (e.g., sensor occlusion), enabling downstream downweighting.\n\nThe combined modality representation prior to fusion incorporates uncertainty modulation:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\tilde{h}_i = (1 - u_i) \\odot h_i,\n\\label{eq:combined}\n\\end{equation}\nwhere $\\odot$ denotes channel-wise multiplication, preserving fault-relevant features while suppressing noise. This design ensures $h_i$ aligns with LLM token dimensions ($D=768$) for seamless integration, with ablation studies confirming 10-12\\% accuracy gains from uncertainty weighting on CWRU datasets \\cite{li2023,wen2024}.\n\n\\subsection{C. Adaptive Cross-Modal Imputation (RAG)}\n\\label{subsec:rag}\n\nMissing or severely degraded modalities pose a significant challenge in industrial diagnostics, where sensor failures or occlusions are common. To address this, we develop an adaptive Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) module that leverages a corpus of clean historical data to impute reliable synthetic samples for unreliable modalities.\n\nThe RAG corpus $\\mathcal{D} = \\{(x_v^j, x_t^j, x_a^j, y^j)\\}_{j=1}^N$ is constructed from high-quality PHM datasets such as CWRU~\\cite{casewestern} and PU bearings~\\cite{pubearings}, totaling $N \\approx 10^5$ samples with balanced fault types. Pre-computed CLIP embeddings~\\cite{radford2021learning} are stored for each modality: $e_i^j = \\phi_{\\text{CLIP}}(x_i^j) \\in \\mathbb{R}^{768}$, enabling fast cross-modal retrieval.\n\nWhen $u_i > \\tau_u = 0.5$ for modality $i$, the module selects the most similar available modality $k = \\arg\\min_{k \\neq i} u_k$ and computes its embedding $e_k = \\phi_{\\text{CLIP}}(x_k)$. Dense retrieval ranks corpus samples by cosine similarity:\n\\begin{equation}\ns_j = \\frac{e_k^\\top e_i^j}{\\|e_k\\| \\cdot \\|e_i^j\\|}, \\quad j^* = \\arg\\max_{j=1}^N s_j.\n\\label{eq:retrieval}\n\\end{equation}\nThe top-3 retrieved samples $\\{x_i^{j_m}\\}_{m=1}^3$ provide context for imputation.\n\nThe RAG retrieval process, illustrated in Fig.~\\ref{fig:4}, refines query construction for better alignment. The query embedding is augmented with prompt information:\n\\begin{equation}\ne_q = \\text{MLP}([\\phi_{\\text{CLIP}}(x_k); \\phi_{\\text{BERT}}(p)], W_q),\n\\label{eq:query}\n\\end{equation}\nwhere $\\phi_{\\text{BERT}}(p)$ encodes the diagnostic prompt $p$, MLP($W_q \\in \\mathbb{R}^{2 \\times 768 \\to 768}$) fuses features. Similarity incorporates uncertainty regularization:\n\\begin{equation}\ns_j = \\cos(e_q, e_i^j) \\cdot (1 - |u_k - u_i^j|),\n\\label{eq:sim}\n\\end{equation}\nRetrieval uses FAISS HNSW index (M=32, efConstruction=200) for top-20 approximation, followed by exact top-k=3 selection via beam search. This dual-stage process improves recall@3 by 15\\% and reduces imputation MSE by 22\\% compared to single-stage dense retrieval.\n\nImputation employs a modality-specific generator $G_i(\\cdot; \\psi_i)$, a lightweight U-Net decoder conditioned on concatenated retrieved data and prompt embeddings:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\hat{x}_i = G_i \\bigl( [\\text{PE}(p); x_k; \\{x_k^{j_m}, x_i^{j_m}\\}_{m=1}^3 ]; \\psi_i \\bigr),\n\\label{eq:imputation}\n\\end{equation}\nwhere $\\text{PE}(p)$ is the positional encoding of a diagnostic prompt $p$ (e.g., ``bearing fault under load''), and $[\\cdot]$ denotes feature concatenation.\n\nReconstruction fidelity is quantified using the 1-Wasserstein distance (optimal transport cost) between $\\hat{x}_i$ and the top retrieved $x_i^{j^*}$:\n\\begin{equation}\nW_1(\\hat{x}_i, x_i^{j^*}) = \\inf_{\\gamma \\in \\Pi(\\mathbb{P}_{\\hat{x}_i}, \\mathbb{P}_{x_i^{j^*}})} \\int \\|z - z'\\| \\, d\\gamma(z, z'),\n\\label{eq:wasserstein}\n\\end{equation}\napproximated efficiently with Sinkhorn-Knopp iterations~\\cite{cuturi2013sinkhorn} (20 iterations, $\\epsilon=0.01$). If $W_1 < \\delta=0.15$ (empirically tuned), $\\hat{x}_i$ is encoded to $\\hat{h}_i, \\hat{u}_i$; else, modality $i$ is masked.\n\nThis cross-modal RAG outperforms naive imputation (e.g., zero-filling, mean) by 12--18\\% in accuracy under 40\\% random modality dropout, surpassing domain-specific diffusion models~\\cite{hoang2020diffusion}. Compared to vanilla RAG~\\cite{lewis2020retrieval}, our CLIP-based retrieval achieves 25\\% higher recall@5 across heterogeneous modalities, as ablated on simulated PU data with thermal occlusion.\n\nThe imputed $\\hat{h}_i$ seamlessly integrates into fusion (Sec.~\\ref{subsec:fusion}), preserving temporal/frequency fault signatures while mitigating distribution shifts from noise.\n\n\\subsection{D. Uncertainty-Aware Fusion}\n\\label{subsec:fusion}\n\nThe encoded representations $\\{\\tilde{h}_i\\}_{i=v,t,a}$ (Eq.~\\eqref{eq:combined}, including imputed $\\hat{h}_i$) are fused into a multimodal embedding $h_f$ via an uncertainty-aware dynamic attention mechanism, which downweights unreliable modalities.\n\nStandard cross-attention in MLLMs~\\cite{lu2024mllm} treats modalities equally, ignoring noise variance. Our approach computes modality reliability scores $\\alpha_i \\in [0,1]$ as:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\alpha_i = \\frac{\\exp(-u_i / \\tau)}{\\sum_{k} \\exp(-u_k / \\tau)},\n\\label{eq:alpha}\n\\end{equation}\nwhere $\\tau=0.1$ is a learnable temperature softening the softmax for gradual weighting. High $u_i$ yields low $\\alpha_i$, adaptively suppressing noisy signals.\n\nFig.~\\ref{fig:5} depicts the fusion architecture. To stabilize weights against outlier uncertainties, a lightweight gating network refines $\\alpha_i$:\n\\begin{equation}\ng_i = \\sigma( W_g [u_i; \\|\\tilde{h}_i\\| ] ), \\quad \\alpha_i' = g_i \\odot \\alpha_i ,\n\\label{eq:gating}\n\\end{equation}\nwith $W_g \\in \\mathbb{R}^{1\\times (1+D)}$, $\\sigma$=sigmoid. The enhanced fusion combines weighted projections and cross-modal attention:\n\\begin{equation}\nh_f = \\sum_i \\alpha_i' \\, \\text{FFN}_i(\\tilde{h}_i) + \\text{MultiHeadCrossAttn}(Q=\\tilde{h}_v, K=V=[\\tilde{h}_t; \\tilde{h}_a]),\n\\label{eq:fusion_enhanced}\n\\end{equation}\nwhere FFN$_i$ (2-layer MLP, ReLU) projects to uniform dim, MultiHeadCrossAttn employs 8 heads ($d_k=96$) with causal masking and rotary positional embeddings (RoPE~\\cite{su2022roformer}) for sequence alignment. Vibration serves as primary query due to its prevalence as ground-truth proxy; thermal/acoustic provide complementary KV. Layer normalization and residuals ($h_f = \\text{LN}(h_f + \\text{Proj}(h_f))$) ensure gradient flow.\n\nThe fused representation is a weighted sum augmented with cross-modal interactions:\n\\begin{equation}\nh_f = \\sum_{i} \\alpha_i \\tilde{h}_i + \\text{CrossAttn}(Q=\\tilde{h}_v, K=\\{\\tilde{h}_t, \\tilde{h}_a\\}, V=\\{\\alpha_t \\tilde{h}_t, \\alpha_a \\tilde{h}_a\\}),\n\\label{eq:fusion}\n\\end{equation}\nwhere CrossAttn follows the scaled dot-product formulation:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\text{Attention}(Q,K,V) = \\text{softmax}\\Bigl( \\frac{QK^\\top}{\\sqrt{d_k}} \\Bigr) V,\n\\label{eq:crossattn}\n\\end{equation}\nwith vibration $h_v$ as query (most reliable baseline) and others as key-value pairs scaled by $\\alpha$. This 8-head multi-head attention (head dim $d_k=96$) captures complementary fault cues (e.g., thermal hotspots aligning with vibration harmonics).\n\n$h_f \\in \\mathbb{R}^{D=768}$ is projected via a linear layer to match LLM token embeddings, prefixed to the diagnostic prompt tokens for fault reasoning. LayerNorm and residual connections stabilize training: $h_f' = \\text{LN}(h_f + \\text{Proj}(h_f))$.\n\nAblations confirm uncertainty weighting boosts F1 by 11\\% over uniform fusion on noisy CWRU (SNR=-5dB), with $\\tau$ ablation showing optimal at 0.08--0.12. Compared to evidential deep ensembles~\\cite{awasthi2023evidential}, our MC-dropout gating is 3x faster at inference ($T=50$ passes).\n\nThis fusion ensures robust $h_f$ under partial observability, enabling the LLM to reason: ``High vibration uncertainty mitigated by thermal confirmation of inner-race fault.''\n\n\\subsection{E. Training: End-to-End and RL Optimization}\n\\label{subsec:training}\n\nThe framework is trained end-to-end on simulated noisy data (20--50\\% modality dropout, Gaussian $\\sigma=0.3$, impulse noise) using a composite loss:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathcal{L} = \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{CE}}(\\hat{y}, y) + \\lambda_1 \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{RAG}} + \\lambda_2 \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{RL}},\n\\label{eq:loss}\n\\end{equation}\nwith $\\lambda_1=0.2$, $\\lambda_2=0.1$. $\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{CE}}$ is cross-entropy over 10 fault classes; $\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{RAG}} = \\mathbb{E}[W_1 + (1-\\text{sim}(\\hat{h}_i, h_i))]$ enforces imputation fidelity; $\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{RL}}$ uses PPO~\\cite{schulman2017ppo} to optimize policy $\\pi_\\theta(a | h_f, p)$ maximizing reward $r = \\text{Acc}(\\hat{y}) - \\beta \\bar{u}_f$, $\\beta=0.5$.\n\nPPO clips surrogate objective with $\\epsilon=0.2$, over 4 epochs per update. Noise simulation via modality masking and augmentation ensures generalization. Training converges in 200 epochs on RTX 4090, achieving 95\\% clean / 82\\% noisy accuracy.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775184983056}}
