{"type":"message","id":"994878bd","parentId":"0a6edcf2","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:23:52.697Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking if the polish (4.6) and de-AI (4.7) stages were completed. Let me check:\n\n1. From the version tracker history, it says \"4.6-done: Writer polished v3 complete (all sections)\" and \"4.7: Writer de-AI v4 complete; truncated method/background/intro restored from v3 → merged v5\"\n2. v4 had truncated sections, v5 was restored from v3\n\nLet me check v3 more carefully to see if it was actually polished or if it's the unpolished version from v2 copy.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_27a07909c4dd4e79aae0b8ed","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check if v3 was actually polished (compare with v2)\nSHARED=\"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9\"\necho \"=== v2 vs v3 word counts ===\"\nfor section in abstract introduction background method experiments conclusion; do\n  v2=$(wc -w < \"$SHARED/drafts/v2/$section.tex\" 2>/dev/null || echo 0)\n  v3=$(wc -w < \"$SHARED/drafts/v3/$section.tex\" 2>/dev/null || echo 0)\n  echo \"  $section: v2=${v2}w → v3=${v3}w\"\ndone\necho \"=== v3 intro sample (check if polished) ===\"\nhead -5 \"$SHARED/drafts/v3/introduction.tex\"\necho \"...\"\necho \"=== v2 intro sample ===\"\nhead -5 \"$SHARED/drafts/v2/introduction.tex\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":552,"output":482,"cacheRead":109312,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":110346,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775193824785}}
{"type":"message","id":"324c996b","parentId":"994878bd","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:23:52.719Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_27a07909c4dd4e79aae0b8ed","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"=== v2 vs v3 word counts ===\n  abstract: v2=178w → v3=178w\n  introduction: v2=812w → v3=812w\n  background: v2=1030w → v3=1030w\n  method: v2=1588w → v3=1635w\n  experiments: v2=2493w → v3=2514w\n  conclusion: v2=202w → v3=202w\n=== v3 intro sample (check if polished) ===\n\\section{Introduction}\n\nRotating machinery, such as bearings, gears, and motors, forms the backbone of modern industrial systems, including power generation, manufacturing, aviation, and petrochemical processes \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. These components are subjected to harsh operating conditions, including high speeds, variable loads, and environmental stressors, leading to inevitable faults like wear, cracks, and imbalances. Undetected faults can escalate into catastrophic failures, resulting in substantial economic losses estimated at billions annually, unplanned downtime, and safety hazards \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Notable incidents underscore this vulnerability: the 2009 gearbox failures at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm affected 80 turbines due to progressive gear wear, causing over 10\\% capacity loss; the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 incident involved an uncontained Rolls-Royce Trent 900 engine failure traced to bearing damage; and the 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 fan blade failure originated from bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}. Traditional fault diagnosis relied on physical models and signal processing techniques, such as Fourier transforms and wavelet analysis. Deep learning revolutionized the field with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit}, achieving superior accuracy on benchmark datasets like CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing} by learning hierarchical representations directly from raw signals \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these advances, single-modality methods struggle with complex fault patterns under varying conditions, underscoring the need for integrated multimodal strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n\nMultimodal data fusion has emerged as a promising paradigm for enhancing fault diagnosis robustness by leveraging complementary information from diverse sensors. Vibration signals captured via accelerometers provide temporal dynamics of mechanical faults; thermal imaging reveals heat anomalies from friction or misalignment; acoustic emissions detect early-stage cracks through high-frequency sounds \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Studies have demonstrated that fusing these modalities via attention mechanisms or graph neural networks improves diagnostic accuracy by 5--10\\% over unimodal baselines, particularly under variable speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. However, industrial deployments face significant challenges: sensor noise from electromagnetic interference and environmental factors corrupts data; partial occlusions or sensor failures lead to missing modalities in up to 50\\% of real-world scenarios. Conventional fusion techniques, such as early or late fusion, assume complete data availability and falter under noise, amplifying errors in cross-modal alignment \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n...\n=== v2 intro sample ===\n\\section{Introduction}\n\nRotating machinery, such as bearings, gears, and motors, forms the backbone of modern industrial systems, including power generation, manufacturing, aviation, and petrochemical processes \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. These components are subjected to harsh operating conditions, including high speeds, variable loads, and environmental stressors, leading to inevitable faults like wear, cracks, and imbalances. Undetected faults can escalate into catastrophic failures, resulting in substantial economic losses estimated at billions annually, unplanned downtime, and safety hazards \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Notable incidents underscore this vulnerability: the 2009 gearbox failures at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm affected 80 turbines due to progressive gear wear, causing over 10\\% capacity loss; the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 incident involved an uncontained Rolls-Royce Trent 900 engine failure traced to bearing damage; and the 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 fan blade failure originated from bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}. Traditional fault diagnosis relied on physical models and signal processing techniques, such as Fourier transforms and wavelet analysis. Deep learning revolutionized the field with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit}, achieving superior accuracy on benchmark datasets like CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing} by learning hierarchical representations directly from raw signals \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these advances, single-modality methods struggle with complex fault patterns under varying conditions, underscoring the need for integrated multimodal strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n\nMultimodal data fusion has emerged as a promising paradigm for enhancing fault diagnosis robustness by leveraging complementary information from diverse sensors. Vibration signals captured via accelerometers provide temporal dynamics of mechanical faults; thermal imaging reveals heat anomalies from friction or misalignment; acoustic emissions detect early-stage cracks through high-frequency sounds \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Studies have demonstrated that fusing these modalities via attention mechanisms or graph neural networks improves diagnostic accuracy by 5--10\\% over unimodal baselines, particularly under variable speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. However, industrial deployments face significant challenges: sensor noise from electromagnetic interference and environmental factors corrupts data; partial occlusions or sensor failures lead to missing modalities in up to 50\\% of real-world scenarios. Conventional fusion techniques, such as early or late fusion, assume complete data availability and falter under noise, amplifying errors in cross-modal alignment \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":18,"aggregated":"=== v2 vs v3 word counts ===\n  abstract: v2=178w → v3=178w\n  introduction: v2=812w → v3=812w\n  background: v2=1030w → v3=1030w\n  method: v2=1588w → v3=1635w\n  experiments: v2=2493w → v3=2514w\n  conclusion: v2=202w → v3=202w\n=== v3 intro sample (check if polished) ===\n\\section{Introduction}\n\nRotating machinery, such as bearings, gears, and motors, forms the backbone of modern industrial systems, including power generation, manufacturing, aviation, and petrochemical processes \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. These components are subjected to harsh operating conditions, including high speeds, variable loads, and environmental stressors, leading to inevitable faults like wear, cracks, and imbalances. Undetected faults can escalate into catastrophic failures, resulting in substantial economic losses estimated at billions annually, unplanned downtime, and safety hazards \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Notable incidents underscore this vulnerability: the 2009 gearbox failures at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm affected 80 turbines due to progressive gear wear, causing over 10\\% capacity loss; the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 incident involved an uncontained Rolls-Royce Trent 900 engine failure traced to bearing damage; and the 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 fan blade failure originated from bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}. Traditional fault diagnosis relied on physical models and signal processing techniques, such as Fourier transforms and wavelet analysis. Deep learning revolutionized the field with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit}, achieving superior accuracy on benchmark datasets like CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing} by learning hierarchical representations directly from raw signals \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these advances, single-modality methods struggle with complex fault patterns under varying conditions, underscoring the need for integrated multimodal strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n\nMultimodal data fusion has emerged as a promising paradigm for enhancing fault diagnosis robustness by leveraging complementary information from diverse sensors. Vibration signals captured via accelerometers provide temporal dynamics of mechanical faults; thermal imaging reveals heat anomalies from friction or misalignment; acoustic emissions detect early-stage cracks through high-frequency sounds \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Studies have demonstrated that fusing these modalities via attention mechanisms or graph neural networks improves diagnostic accuracy by 5--10\\% over unimodal baselines, particularly under variable speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. However, industrial deployments face significant challenges: sensor noise from electromagnetic interference and environmental factors corrupts data; partial occlusions or sensor failures lead to missing modalities in up to 50\\% of real-world scenarios. Conventional fusion techniques, such as early or late fusion, assume complete data availability and falter under noise, amplifying errors in cross-modal alignment \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n...\n=== v2 intro sample ===\n\\section{Introduction}\n\nRotating machinery, such as bearings, gears, and motors, forms the backbone of modern industrial systems, including power generation, manufacturing, aviation, and petrochemical processes \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. These components are subjected to harsh operating conditions, including high speeds, variable loads, and environmental stressors, leading to inevitable faults like wear, cracks, and imbalances. Undetected faults can escalate into catastrophic failures, resulting in substantial economic losses estimated at billions annually, unplanned downtime, and safety hazards \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Notable incidents underscore this vulnerability: the 2009 gearbox failures at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm affected 80 turbines due to progressive gear wear, causing over 10\\% capacity loss; the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 incident involved an uncontained Rolls-Royce Trent 900 engine failure traced to bearing damage; and the 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 fan blade failure originated from bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}. Traditional fault diagnosis relied on physical models and signal processing techniques, such as Fourier transforms and wavelet analysis. Deep learning revolutionized the field with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit}, achieving superior accuracy on benchmark datasets like CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing} by learning hierarchical representations directly from raw signals \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these advances, single-modality methods struggle with complex fault patterns under varying conditions, underscoring the need for integrated multimodal strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n\nMultimodal data fusion has emerged as a promising paradigm for enhancing fault diagnosis robustness by leveraging complementary information from diverse sensors. Vibration signals captured via accelerometers provide temporal dynamics of mechanical faults; thermal imaging reveals heat anomalies from friction or misalignment; acoustic emissions detect early-stage cracks through high-frequency sounds \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Studies have demonstrated that fusing these modalities via attention mechanisms or graph neural networks improves diagnostic accuracy by 5--10\\% over unimodal baselines, particularly under variable speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. However, industrial deployments face significant challenges: sensor noise from electromagnetic interference and environmental factors corrupts data; partial occlusions or sensor failures lead to missing modalities in up to 50\\% of real-world scenarios. Conventional fusion techniques, such as early or late fusion, assume complete data availability and falter under noise, amplifying errors in cross-modal alignment \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775193832717}}
{"type":"message","id":"0b9ab9cd","parentId":"324c996b","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:24:05.088Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The v2 and v3 introduction files are identical! The polish task truncated them and I restored from v2. So v3 intro and background are identical to v2 (no polish applied). Method and experiments did get some changes (method: 1588→1635, experiments: 2493→2514).\n\nThe de-AI process (4.7) created v4 which was truncated, and v5 was a merge that also had issues.\n\nSo the honest answer is:\n- 4.6 polish: Partially completed. Method and experiments got some polish (slight word count changes). Intro, background, abstract, conclusion were restored from v2 after Writer truncated them.\n\n\n- 4.7 de-AI: Had the same problem—v4 ended up truncated, v5 merged with issues.\n\nThe writing is solid though, even if the polish and de-AI didn't fully materialize. That's pretty typical of how these automated stages actually play out. I'll just move forward with v3 as my final version and keep it straightforward.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"坦白说，**两个阶段都没有完整执行**。\n\n实际情况：\n- **4.6 润色**：Writer 润色时截短了 intro（812→624w）和 background（1030→573w），我从 v2 恢复了。Method 和 experiments 有小幅变化（1588→1635w, 2493→2514w），但 intro/background/conclusion/abstract 实质上**没被润色**。\n- **4.7 去 AI 痕迹**：v4 被截得更严重（intro 732w, method 1316w），v5 恢复后也有些损失（conclusion 202→172w）。API 故障也中断了部分任务。\n\n**原因**：这是已知问题（P8 教训）—— Writer 在\"润色/去 AI\"任务中倾向于删减而非保留。手动从 v2 恢复后内容质量其实已经不错。\n\n**你的选择**：\n1. **直接继续** — v3 内容质量可接受，跳过 4.6/4.7 直接进入阶段 5（Editor 整合 paper.tex）\n2. **让我手动润色** — Leader 逐 section 做轻度润色（保证不截短，但需要几分钟）\n\n哪种？"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":1887,"output":766,"cacheRead":109824,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":112477,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775193832720}}
