{"type":"message","id":"70b1baf9","parentId":"8b4da00c","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:13.661Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Very few AI phrases found! The writing is already quite clean. Let me check more specifically.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_468a57d080e542648f31cfad","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"SHARED=\"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3\"\n# Check exact locations of remaining AI phrases\necho \"=== state-of-the-art ===\"\ngrep -rn \"state-of-the-art\" \"$SHARED\"/*.tex\necho \"=== Additionally ===\"\ngrep -rn \"Additionally\" \"$SHARED\"/*.tex\necho \"=== Other patterns ===\"\ngrep -rn \"plays a.*role\" \"$SHARED\"/*.tex\ngrep -rn \"have attracted\" \"$SHARED\"/*.tex\ngrep -rn \"is worth noting\" \"$SHARED\"/*.tex\ngrep -rn \"it should be noted\" \"$SHARED\"/*.tex","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":481,"output":216,"cacheRead":117760,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":118457,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775194748320}}
{"type":"message","id":"fc907763","parentId":"70b1baf9","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:13.672Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_468a57d080e542648f31cfad","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"=== state-of-the-art ===\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/abstract.tex:9:Experiments conducted on benchmark datasets show that RobustMLLM-Diag exceeds state-of-the-art methods by more than 15\\% in accuracy under conditions of 50\\% noise corruption and modality dropout. Such performance enables dependable deployment in safety-critical rotating machinery, markedly progressing prognostics and health management in industrial contexts.\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/conclusion.tex:4:This paper presents RobustMLLM-Diag, a novel Multimodal Large Language Model designed for robust fault diagnosis in rotating machinery under conditions of noisy and incomplete multimodal data. Our framework addresses critical industrial challenges via four key contributions: (1) an adaptive cross-modal Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) module that imputes missing modalities by retrieving and synthesizing from a corpus of clean historical data using multimodal prompts; (2) an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism leveraging Bayesian Monte Carlo dropout for epistemic uncertainty quantification and dynamic modality weighting during fusion; (3) an end-to-end training strategy augmented with Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) reinforcement learning to refine diagnostic policies under simulated noise and dropout perturbations; and (4) rigorous empirical validation on the CWRU and Paderborn benchmarks, demonstrating superior accuracy (96.2\\% on CWRU clean, 91.3\\% noisy) and robustness, outperforming state-of-the-art baselines by over 15\\% across 20-50\\% noise and missing modality scenarios.\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex:4:This section evaluates the RobustMLLM-Diag framework on benchmark and industrial datasets under noisy and incomplete multimodal conditions. The framework exhibits superior robustness compared to state-of-the-art baselines, particularly in high-noise (SNR $-5$ dB) and high-missing-ratio (50\\%) scenarios.\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex:45:To benchmark RobustMLLM-Diag against state-of-the-art methods, we compare it with six representative baselines, including vision-language models (VLMs), traditional multimodal fusion strategies, and unimodal specialists. All baselines use the same modality encoders and Vicuna-7B LLM backbone (where applicable) as our approach, ensuring a fair comparison under identical noisy and missing conditions. This setup highlights the contributions of our adaptive imputation and uncertainty-aware fusion techniques.\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/introduction.tex:5:Early fault diagnosis methodologies predominantly depended on physics-based modeling coupled with classical signal processing techniques, including Fourier transforms for frequency-domain analysis and wavelet transforms for time-frequency localization. The integration of deep learning paradigms has markedly advanced this domain, with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit} achieving state-of-the-art results on established benchmark datasets such as CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing}. These architectures autonomously derive multi-level hierarchical feature representations from raw vibration signals and other sensor data \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these strides, methods relying on a single modality often struggle to capture the full spectrum of complex fault patterns, particularly in scenarios involving fluctuating operational parameters, thereby necessitating the adoption of multimodal fusion strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n=== Additionally ===\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex:9:To comprehensively evaluate the generalization and robustness of the RobustMLLM-Diag framework across diverse industrial scenarios, we perform experiments on two established public bearing fault diagnosis benchmarks: the Case Western Reserve University (CWRU) dataset \\cite{cwrudataset} and the Paderborn University (PU) Bearing dataset \\cite{pubearing}, both augmented with synthetic thermal images and acoustic emissions to emulate real-world multimodal data streams. Additionally, we introduce a proprietary industrial dataset derived from wind turbine drivetrains (WT-Industrial), capturing authentic deployment conditions.\n=== Other patterns ===\n\n(Command exited with code 1)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":1,"durationMs":7,"aggregated":"=== state-of-the-art ===\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/abstract.tex:9:Experiments conducted on benchmark datasets show that RobustMLLM-Diag exceeds state-of-the-art methods by more than 15\\% in accuracy under conditions of 50\\% noise corruption and modality dropout. Such performance enables dependable deployment in safety-critical rotating machinery, markedly progressing prognostics and health management in industrial contexts.\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/conclusion.tex:4:This paper presents RobustMLLM-Diag, a novel Multimodal Large Language Model designed for robust fault diagnosis in rotating machinery under conditions of noisy and incomplete multimodal data. Our framework addresses critical industrial challenges via four key contributions: (1) an adaptive cross-modal Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) module that imputes missing modalities by retrieving and synthesizing from a corpus of clean historical data using multimodal prompts; (2) an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism leveraging Bayesian Monte Carlo dropout for epistemic uncertainty quantification and dynamic modality weighting during fusion; (3) an end-to-end training strategy augmented with Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) reinforcement learning to refine diagnostic policies under simulated noise and dropout perturbations; and (4) rigorous empirical validation on the CWRU and Paderborn benchmarks, demonstrating superior accuracy (96.2\\% on CWRU clean, 91.3\\% noisy) and robustness, outperforming state-of-the-art baselines by over 15\\% across 20-50\\% noise and missing modality scenarios.\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex:4:This section evaluates the RobustMLLM-Diag framework on benchmark and industrial datasets under noisy and incomplete multimodal conditions. The framework exhibits superior robustness compared to state-of-the-art baselines, particularly in high-noise (SNR $-5$ dB) and high-missing-ratio (50\\%) scenarios.\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex:45:To benchmark RobustMLLM-Diag against state-of-the-art methods, we compare it with six representative baselines, including vision-language models (VLMs), traditional multimodal fusion strategies, and unimodal specialists. All baselines use the same modality encoders and Vicuna-7B LLM backbone (where applicable) as our approach, ensuring a fair comparison under identical noisy and missing conditions. This setup highlights the contributions of our adaptive imputation and uncertainty-aware fusion techniques.\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/introduction.tex:5:Early fault diagnosis methodologies predominantly depended on physics-based modeling coupled with classical signal processing techniques, including Fourier transforms for frequency-domain analysis and wavelet transforms for time-frequency localization. The integration of deep learning paradigms has markedly advanced this domain, with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit} achieving state-of-the-art results on established benchmark datasets such as CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing}. These architectures autonomously derive multi-level hierarchical feature representations from raw vibration signals and other sensor data \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these strides, methods relying on a single modality often struggle to capture the full spectrum of complex fault patterns, particularly in scenarios involving fluctuating operational parameters, thereby necessitating the adoption of multimodal fusion strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n=== Additionally ===\n/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex:9:To comprehensively evaluate the generalization and robustness of the RobustMLLM-Diag framework across diverse industrial scenarios, we perform experiments on two established public bearing fault diagnosis benchmarks: the Case Western Reserve University (CWRU) dataset \\cite{cwrudataset} and the Paderborn University (PU) Bearing dataset \\cite{pubearing}, both augmented with synthetic thermal images and acoustic emissions to emulate real-world multimodal data streams. Additionally, we introduce a proprietary industrial dataset derived from wind turbine drivetrains (WT-Industrial), capturing authentic deployment conditions.\n=== Other patterns ===\n\n(Command exited with code 1)","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775194753670}}
{"type":"message","id":"8fc560b1","parentId":"fc907763","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:24.535Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The AI phrases are minimal. \"state-of-the-art\" appears 5 times - this is a standard academic term and not really \"AI-speak\" in academic context. \"Additionally\" appears once. \"novel\" appears in conclusion. The writing is actually quite clean already.\n\nLet me replace \"state-of-the-art\" with alternatives in a few places and \"Additionally\" with something else, then declare 4.7 done. I'll do targeted edits.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Writing is already quite clean. Just a few minor fixes needed:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a98be286a7ce42b5a61a7f28","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/abstract.tex","old_string":"Experiments conducted on benchmark datasets show that RobustMLLM-Diag exceeds state-of-the-art methods by more than 15\\%","new_string":"Experiments conducted on benchmark datasets show that RobustMLLM-Diag exceeds existing methods by more than 15\\%"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":1245,"output":318,"cacheRead":118208,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":119771,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775194753673}}
{"type":"message","id":"709fb18c","parentId":"8fc560b1","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:24.540Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_a98be286a7ce42b5a61a7f28","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/abstract.tex."}],"details":{"diff":"    ...\n  5 RobustMLLM-Diag introduces an MLLM framework tailored for resilient fault diagnosis. The approach incorporates Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) for adaptive cross-modal imputation that reconstructs missing data, coupled with an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism to facilitate robust feature fusion.\n  6 \n  7 Among its key features are Bayesian dropout for uncertainty quantification, dynamic weighting of modalities according to their reliability, and reinforcement learning to enhance robustness against varying noise levels.\n  8 \n- 9 Experiments conducted on benchmark datasets show that RobustMLLM-Diag exceeds state-of-the-art methods by more than 15\\% in accuracy under conditions of 50\\% noise corruption and modality dropout. Such performance enables dependable deployment in safety-critical rotating machinery, markedly progressing prognostics and health management in industrial contexts.\n+ 9 Experiments conducted on benchmark datasets show that RobustMLLM-Diag exceeds existing methods by more than 15\\% in accuracy under conditions of 50\\% noise corruption and modality dropout. Such performance enables dependable deployment in safety-critical rotating machinery, markedly progressing prognostics and health management in industrial contexts.\n 10 \n 11 \\begin{IEEEkeywords}\n 12 Multimodal large language model, fault diagnosis, cross-modal imputation, uncertainty-aware fusion, Bayesian dropout, dynamic modality weighting, reinforcement learning, prognostics and health management\n 13 \\end{IEEEkeywords}","firstChangedLine":9},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775194764538}}
{"type":"message","id":"7934402a","parentId":"709fb18c","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:30.489Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me continue with the remaining edits. I'll replace \"state-of-the-art\" in a few more places where it's redundant.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_f0d03683720041e6bd725a5b","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex","new_string":"The framework exhibits superior robustness compared to baseline methods, particularly in high-noise","old_string":"The framework exhibits superior robustness compared to state-of-the-art baselines, particularly in high-noise"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":295,"output":152,"cacheRead":119424,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":119871,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775194764540}}
{"type":"message","id":"3b205a52","parentId":"7934402a","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:30.496Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_f0d03683720041e6bd725a5b","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex."}],"details":{"diff":"   1 \\section{Experiments}\n   2 \\label{sec:experiments}\n   3 \n-  4 This section evaluates the RobustMLLM-Diag framework on benchmark and industrial datasets under noisy and incomplete multimodal conditions. The framework exhibits superior robustness compared to state-of-the-art baselines, particularly in high-noise (SNR $-5$ dB) and high-missing-ratio (50\\%) scenarios.\n+  4 This section evaluates the RobustMLLM-Diag framework on benchmark and industrial datasets under noisy and incomplete multimodal conditions. The framework exhibits superior robustness compared to baseline methods, particularly in high-noise (SNR $-5$ dB) and high-missing-ratio (50\\%) scenarios.\n   5 \n   6 \\subsection{A. Datasets and Setup}\n   7 \\label{subsec:datasets}\n   8 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":4},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775194770493}}
