{"type":"message","id":"b2835ca4","parentId":"bfe7d83a","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:35.321Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_bface41a5a3845f49f198985","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  41 \n  42 \\subsection{B. Baselines and Metrics}\n  43 \\label{subsec:baselines}\n  44 \n- 45 To benchmark RobustMLLM-Diag against state-of-the-art methods, we compare it with six representative baselines, including vision-language models (VLMs), traditional multimodal fusion strategies, and unimodal specialists. All baselines use the same modality encoders and Vicuna-7B LLM backbone (where applicable) as our approach, ensuring a fair comparison under identical noisy and missing conditions. This setup highlights the contributions of our adaptive imputation and uncertainty-aware fusion techniques.\n+ 45 To benchmark RobustMLLM-Diag against leading methods, we compare it with six representative baselines, including vision-language models (VLMs), traditional multimodal fusion strategies, and unimodal specialists. All baselines use the same modality encoders and Vicuna-7B LLM backbone (where applicable) as our approach, ensuring a fair comparison under identical noisy and missing conditions. This setup highlights the contributions of our adaptive imputation and uncertainty-aware fusion techniques.\n  46 \n  47 \\begin{itemize}\n  48 \\item \\textbf{LLaVA-1.5} \\cite{llava}: A general-purpose vision-language model finetuned end-to-end on fault diagnosis prompts combining textual descriptions with multimodal inputs.\n  49 \\item \\textbf{BLIP-2} \\cite{blip2}: Bootstrapped language-image pretraining model, adapted for multimodal classification via query generation.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":45},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775194775318}}
{"type":"message","id":"6dc8f5fc","parentId":"b2835ca4","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:39.553Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now replace \"Additionally\" with something more natural.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_dc9f497401c24bf3a552a5a1","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex","new_string":"We also introduce a proprietary industrial dataset derived from wind turbine drivetrains","old_string":"Additionally, we introduce a proprietary industrial dataset derived from wind turbine drivetrains"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":189,"output":112,"cacheRead":119872,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":120173,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775194775321}}
{"type":"message","id":"f22d9532","parentId":"6dc8f5fc","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:39.558Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_dc9f497401c24bf3a552a5a1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/experiments.tex."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n   5 \n   6 \\subsection{A. Datasets and Setup}\n   7 \\label{subsec:datasets}\n   8 \n-  9 To comprehensively evaluate the generalization and robustness of the RobustMLLM-Diag framework across diverse industrial scenarios, we perform experiments on two established public bearing fault diagnosis benchmarks: the Case Western Reserve University (CWRU) dataset \\cite{cwrudataset} and the Paderborn University (PU) Bearing dataset \\cite{pubearing}, both augmented with synthetic thermal images and acoustic emissions to emulate real-world multimodal data streams. Additionally, we introduce a proprietary industrial dataset derived from wind turbine drivetrains (WT-Industrial), capturing authentic deployment conditions.\n+  9 To comprehensively evaluate the generalization and robustness of the RobustMLLM-Diag framework across diverse industrial scenarios, we perform experiments on two established public bearing fault diagnosis benchmarks: the Case Western Reserve University (CWRU) dataset \\cite{cwrudataset} and the Paderborn University (PU) Bearing dataset \\cite{pubearing}, both augmented with synthetic thermal images and acoustic emissions to emulate real-world multimodal data streams. We also introduce a proprietary industrial dataset derived from wind turbine drivetrains (WT-Industrial), capturing authentic deployment conditions.\n  10 \n  11 The \\textbf{CWRU Dataset} comprises vibration signals acquired from a motor-driven mechanical fault simulator operating at a consistent 12 kHz sampling rate. It encompasses 10 distinct fault classes: one normal condition and nine faulty states, including inner race (IR) faults at three severity levels (0.007\", 0.014\", 0.021\"), outer race (OR) faults at three levels, and ball (B) faults at three levels, under varying load conditions from 0 to 3 horsepower. To create multimodal inputs, thermal images are simulated using finite element analysis (FEA) to model fault-induced frictional heat patterns, resized to $224\\times224$ RGB format. Acoustic emissions are generated from microphone recordings of the simulator, transformed into Mel-spectrograms with 128 Mel frequency bins and 1024-point short-time Fourier transform (STFT) windows (hop length 512). This augmentation yields a total of 12,000 balanced samples, ensuring representation across all classes and motor speeds.\n  12 \n  13 The \\textbf{PU Bearing Dataset} provides more realistic degradation profiles from 32 bearings tested under diverse load and speed combinations, sampled at 64 kHz. Fault classes include healthy bearings, three types of artificial damages (e.g., pin prick, laser pit), and two accelerated lifetime faults exhibiting progressive wear. Multimodal augmentation follows the CWRU protocol, adapted for PU's higher resolution, resulting in 8 classes and approximately 5,000 samples. This dataset is particularly valuable for evaluating gradual fault progression under variable operating conditions.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":9},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775194779555}}
{"type":"message","id":"2d6b6e1d","parentId":"f22d9532","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:46.444Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me also replace the one in introduction.tex about \"state-of-the-art results\".","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2d07a46dc12b4f90b53a99f1","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/introduction.tex","new_string":"achieving leading results on established benchmark datasets","old_string":"achieving state-of-the-art results on established benchmark datasets"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":205,"output":117,"cacheRead":120000,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":120322,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775194779558}}
{"type":"message","id":"d3daa571","parentId":"2d6b6e1d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:46.448Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_2d07a46dc12b4f90b53a99f1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/introduction.tex."}],"details":{"diff":"  1 \\section{Introduction}\n  2 \n  3 Rotating machinery, including critical components such as bearings, gears, and motors, serves as the foundational element of modern industrial infrastructures. These systems span a wide array of applications, from power generation facilities and manufacturing plants to aviation operations and petrochemical processing units \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. Operating under rigorous conditions---characterized by elevated rotational speeds, dynamic load variations, and harsh environmental influences---these components are prone to developing faults, including material wear, structural cracks, and dynamic imbalances. When such faults remain undetected, they can escalate rapidly into catastrophic system failures, incurring enormous economic repercussions estimated in the billions of dollars each year, alongside extensive unplanned downtime and profound safety risks to personnel and assets \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Real-world incidents poignantly illustrate this susceptibility. For example, the 2009 gearbox malfunctions at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm compromised 80 turbines, primarily due to progressive gear wear that resulted in more than 10\\% loss of overall capacity. Similarly, the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 experienced an uncontained engine failure in a Rolls-Royce Trent 900, which was later traced to initial bearing degradation. The 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 incident, involving fan blade detachment, was likewise rooted in bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}.\n  4 \n- 5 Early fault diagnosis methodologies predominantly depended on physics-based modeling coupled with classical signal processing techniques, including Fourier transforms for frequency-domain analysis and wavelet transforms for time-frequency localization. The integration of deep learning paradigms has markedly advanced this domain, with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit} achieving state-of-the-art results on established benchmark datasets such as CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing}. These architectures autonomously derive multi-level hierarchical feature representations from raw vibration signals and other sensor data \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these strides, methods relying on a single modality often struggle to capture the full spectrum of complex fault patterns, particularly in scenarios involving fluctuating operational parameters, thereby necessitating the adoption of multimodal fusion strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n+ 5 Early fault diagnosis methodologies predominantly depended on physics-based modeling coupled with classical signal processing techniques, including Fourier transforms for frequency-domain analysis and wavelet transforms for time-frequency localization. The integration of deep learning paradigms has markedly advanced this domain, with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit} achieving leading results on established benchmark datasets such as CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing}. These architectures autonomously derive multi-level hierarchical feature representations from raw vibration signals and other sensor data \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these strides, methods relying on a single modality often struggle to capture the full spectrum of complex fault patterns, particularly in scenarios involving fluctuating operational parameters, thereby necessitating the adoption of multimodal fusion strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n  6 \n  7 Multimodal data fusion has gained prominence as a potent methodology to augment the reliability and accuracy of fault diagnosis by exploiting synergistic information from diverse sensor types. Vibration signals, acquired through accelerometers, encapsulate the temporal evolution of mechanical disturbances; thermal imaging unveils anomalous heat patterns stemming from frictional losses or misalignment; and acoustic emission monitoring identifies nascent cracks through characteristic high-frequency emissions \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Empirical investigations reveal that advanced fusion techniques---employing attention-based mechanisms or graph neural networks---consistently deliver accuracy enhancements of 5\\% to 10\\% relative to unimodal approaches, with pronounced benefits observed under non-stationary conditions like varying speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. Nevertheless, practical deployment in industrial environments introduces substantial hurdles. Sensor data is frequently contaminated by noise arising from electromagnetic interference, mechanical vibrations, or ambient factors; moreover, partial occlusions, sensor malfunctions, or data transmission failures lead to missing modalities in as many as 50\\% of operational instances. Conventional fusion schemes, whether early concatenation or late decision-level integration, presuppose complete and clean data availability, rendering them vulnerable to misalignment errors exacerbated by noise \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n  8 \n  9 The evolution toward multimodal large language models (MLLMs) introduces a sophisticated layer of capability, harnessing extensive vision-language pretraining to process and reason over images, spectrograms, and descriptive text. Prominent exemplars include LLaVA \\cite{liu2023llava,lu2024}, BLIP-2 \\cite{blip2}, Flamingo \\cite{flamingo}, and Qwen-VL \\cite{qwen}, which showcase exceptional zero-shot generalization on everyday natural images. In the specialized realm of industrial fault diagnosis, however, these models encounter pronounced limitations: artifacts prevalent in spectrograms derived from vibration data perplex visual encoders; thermal images, lacking structured semantic cues, incite erroneous hallucinations during fault localization; and rigorous evaluations on prognostics and health management (PHM) datasets document accuracy degradations of 15--20\\% in noisy regimes---for instance, LLaVA's bearing fault classification accuracy declining from 92\\% to 74\\% at 20 dB signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), alongside Qwen-VL's thermal anomaly detection falling from 88\\% to 70\\% in dusty operational contexts \\cite{hoang2025,kim2024,lu2024}.\n    ...","firstChangedLine":5},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775194786446}}
{"type":"message","id":"6a0a494a","parentId":"d3daa571","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:53.749Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now let me also replace \"state-of-the-art baselines\" in conclusion.tex.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_d8f38df870ec468e9a5bbd05","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/conclusion.tex","new_string":"outperforming existing baselines by over 15\\%","old_string":"outperforming state-of-the-art baselines by over 15\\%"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":155,"output":129,"cacheRead":120192,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":120476,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775194786449}}
{"type":"message","id":"366963fb","parentId":"6a0a494a","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:39:53.753Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_d8f38df870ec468e9a5bbd05","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/conclusion.tex."}],"details":{"diff":" 1 \\section{Conclusion}\n 2 \\label{sec:conclusion}\n 3 \n-4 This paper presents RobustMLLM-Diag, a novel Multimodal Large Language Model designed for robust fault diagnosis in rotating machinery under conditions of noisy and incomplete multimodal data. Our framework addresses critical industrial challenges via four key contributions: (1) an adaptive cross-modal Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) module that imputes missing modalities by retrieving and synthesizing from a corpus of clean historical data using multimodal prompts; (2) an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism leveraging Bayesian Monte Carlo dropout for epistemic uncertainty quantification and dynamic modality weighting during fusion; (3) an end-to-end training strategy augmented with Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) reinforcement learning to refine diagnostic policies under simulated noise and dropout perturbations; and (4) rigorous empirical validation on the CWRU and Paderborn benchmarks, demonstrating superior accuracy (96.2\\% on CWRU clean, 91.3\\% noisy) and robustness, outperforming state-of-the-art baselines by over 15\\% across 20-50\\% noise and missing modality scenarios.\n+4 This paper presents RobustMLLM-Diag, a novel Multimodal Large Language Model designed for robust fault diagnosis in rotating machinery under conditions of noisy and incomplete multimodal data. Our framework addresses critical industrial challenges via four key contributions: (1) an adaptive cross-modal Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) module that imputes missing modalities by retrieving and synthesizing from a corpus of clean historical data using multimodal prompts; (2) an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism leveraging Bayesian Monte Carlo dropout for epistemic uncertainty quantification and dynamic modality weighting during fusion; (3) an end-to-end training strategy augmented with Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) reinforcement learning to refine diagnostic policies under simulated noise and dropout perturbations; and (4) rigorous empirical validation on the CWRU and Paderborn benchmarks, demonstrating superior accuracy (96.2\\% on CWRU clean, 91.3\\% noisy) and robustness, outperforming existing baselines by over 15\\% across 20-50\\% noise and missing modality scenarios.\n 5 \n 6 Ablation studies confirm the indispensable role of each component, with synergistic gains evident in t-SNE visualizations and confusion matrices that underscore precise fault discrimination.\n 7 \n 8 Future research directions include real-time deployment on edge devices in factories, integration of additional modalities such as motor current signatures and oil debris analysis, and federated learning paradigms to support collaborative diagnostics while preserving data privacy across distributed manufacturing sites.","firstChangedLine":4},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775194793751}}
