{"type":"message","id":"11bd24e2","parentId":"42bd4960","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:40:07.202Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_29e01592c2b847d9ad4e99bb","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/conclusion.tex."}],"details":{"diff":" 1 \\section{Conclusion}\n 2 \\label{sec:conclusion}\n 3 \n-4 This paper presents RobustMLLM-Diag, a novel Multimodal Large Language Model designed for robust fault diagnosis in rotating machinery under conditions of noisy and incomplete multimodal data. Our framework addresses critical industrial challenges via four key contributions: (1) an adaptive cross-modal Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) module that imputes missing modalities by retrieving and synthesizing from a corpus of clean historical data using multimodal prompts; (2) an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism leveraging Bayesian Monte Carlo dropout for epistemic uncertainty quantification and dynamic modality weighting during fusion; (3) an end-to-end training strategy augmented with Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) reinforcement learning to refine diagnostic policies under simulated noise and dropout perturbations; and (4) rigorous empirical validation on the CWRU and Paderborn benchmarks, demonstrating superior accuracy (96.2\\% on CWRU clean, 91.3\\% noisy) and robustness, outperforming existing baselines by over 15\\% across 20-50\\% noise and missing modality scenarios.\n+4 This work presents RobustMLLM-Diag, a Multimodal Large Language Model designed for robust fault diagnosis in rotating machinery under conditions of noisy and incomplete multimodal data. Our framework addresses critical industrial challenges via four key contributions: (1) an adaptive cross-modal Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) module that imputes missing modalities by retrieving and synthesizing from a corpus of clean historical data using multimodal prompts; (2) an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism leveraging Bayesian Monte Carlo dropout for epistemic uncertainty quantification and dynamic modality weighting during fusion; (3) an end-to-end training strategy augmented with Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) reinforcement learning to refine diagnostic policies under simulated noise and dropout perturbations; and (4) rigorous empirical validation on the CWRU and Paderborn benchmarks, demonstrating superior accuracy (96.2\\% on CWRU clean, 91.3\\% noisy) and robustness, outperforming existing baselines by over 15\\% across 20-50\\% noise and missing modality scenarios.\n 5 \n 6 Ablation studies confirm the indispensable role of each component, with synergistic gains evident in t-SNE visualizations and confusion matrices that underscore precise fault discrimination.\n 7 \n 8 Future research directions include real-time deployment on edge devices in factories, integration of additional modalities such as motor current signatures and oil debris analysis, and federated learning paradigms to support collaborative diagnostics while preserving data privacy across distributed manufacturing sites.","firstChangedLine":4},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775194807198}}
