{"type":"message","id":"a9def2a1","parentId":"d159f01c","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:45:51.615Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_10ea4a40200648f895369fc1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\\documentclass[lettersize,journal]{IEEEtran}\n\\usepackage{amsmath,amsfonts}\n\\usepackage{algorithmic}\n\\usepackage{algorithm}\n\\usepackage{array}\n\\usepackage[caption=false,font=normalsize,labelfont=sf,textfont=sf]{subfig}\n\\usepackage{textcomp}\n\\usepackage{stfloats}\n\\usepackage{url}\n\\usepackage{verbatim}\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\usepackage{cite}\n\\hyphenation{op-tical net-works semi-conduc-tor IEEE-Xplore}\n% updated with editorial comments 8/9/2021\n\n\\begin{document}\n\n\\title{A Sample Article Using IEEEtran.cls\\\\ for IEEE Journals and Transactions}\n\n\\author{IEEE Publication Technology,~\\IEEEmembership{Staff,~IEEE,}\n        % <-this % stops a space\n\\thanks{This paper was produced by the IEEE Publication Technology Group. They are in Piscataway, NJ.}% <-this % stops a space\n\\thanks{Manuscript received April 19, 2021; revised August 16, 2021.}}\n\n% The paper headers\n\\markboth{Journal of \\LaTeX\\ Class Files,~Vol.~14, No.~8, August~2021}%\n{Shell \\MakeLowercase{\\textit{et al.}}: A Sample Article Using IEEEtran.cls for IEEE Journals}\n\n\\IEEEpubid{0000--0000/00\\$00.00~\\copyright~2021 IEEE}\n% Remember, if you use this you must call \\IEEEpubidadjcol in the second\n% column for its text to clear the IEEEpubid mark.\n\n\\maketitle\n\n\\begin{abstract}\nThis document describes the most common article elements and how to use the IEEEtran class with \\LaTeX \\ to produce files that are suitable for submission to the IEEE.  IEEEtran can produce conference, journal, and technical note (correspondence) papers with a suitable choice of class options. \n\\end{abstract}\n\n\\begin{IEEEkeywords}\nArticle submission, IEEE, IEEEtran, journal, \\LaTeX, paper, template, typesetting.\n\\end{IEEEkeywords}\n\n\\section{Introduction}\n\\IEEEPARstart{T}{his} file is intended to serve as a ``sample article file''\nfor IEEE journal papers produced under \\LaTeX\\ using\nIEEEtran.cls version 1.8b and later. The most common elements are covered in the simplified and updated instructions in ``New\\_IEEEtran\\_how-to.pdf''. For less common elements you can refer back to the original ``IEEEtran\\_HOWTO.pdf''. It is assumed that the reader has a basic working knowledge of \\LaTeX. Those who are new to \\LaTeX \\ are encouraged to read Tobias Oetiker's ``The Not So Short Introduction to \\LaTeX ,'' available at: \\url{http://tug.ctan.org/info/lshort/english/lshort.pdf} which provides an overview of working with \\LaTeX.\n\n\\section{The Design, Intent, and \\\\ Limitations of the Templates}\nThe templates are intended to {\\bf{approximate the final look and page length of the articles/papers}}. {\\bf{They are NOT intended to be the final produced work that is displayed in print or on IEEEXplore\\textsuperscript{\\textregistered}}}. They will help to give the authors an approximation of the number of pages that will be in the final version. The structure of the \\LaTeX\\ files, as designed, enable easy conversion to XML for the composition systems used by the IEEE. The XML files are used to produce the final print/IEEEXplore pdf and then converted to HTML for IEEEXplore.\n\n\n[568 more lines in file. Use offset=51 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775195151612}}
{"type":"message","id":"9e00f212","parentId":"a9def2a1","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:45:57.162Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, I have the template structure. Now I need to create the paper.tex file. Let me assemble all sections together. I'll create it with the standard IEEE template structure.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_cd6d8c291d40496eb3c91ecf","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/abstract.tex"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":996,"output":118,"cacheRead":122304,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":123418,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775195151615}}
{"type":"message","id":"e09213d0","parentId":"9e00f212","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:45:57.169Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_cd6d8c291d40496eb3c91ecf","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Industrial fault diagnosis is challenged by noisy and incomplete multimodal data, encompassing vibration signals, thermal images, acoustic emissions, and spectra. Typically, 20-50\\% of these modalities are missing or corrupted owing to sensor failures or environmental noise.\n\nPrevailing Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) depend on inflexible fusion strategies ill-equipped to handle input uncertainties, which erodes diagnostic precision.\n\nRobustMLLM-Diag introduces an MLLM framework tailored for resilient fault diagnosis. The approach incorporates Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) for adaptive cross-modal imputation that reconstructs missing data, coupled with an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism to facilitate robust feature fusion.\n\nAmong its key features are Bayesian dropout for uncertainty quantification, dynamic weighting of modalities according to their reliability, and reinforcement learning to enhance robustness against varying noise levels.\n\nExperiments conducted on benchmark datasets show that RobustMLLM-Diag exceeds existing methods by more than 15\\% in accuracy under conditions of 50\\% noise corruption and modality dropout. Such performance enables dependable deployment in safety-critical rotating machinery, markedly progressing prognostics and health management in industrial contexts.\n\n\\begin{IEEEkeywords}\nMultimodal large language model, fault diagnosis, cross-modal imputation, uncertainty-aware fusion, Bayesian dropout, dynamic modality weighting, reinforcement learning, prognostics and health management\n\\end{IEEEkeywords}"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775195157166}}
{"type":"message","id":"c9129d13","parentId":"e09213d0","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:46:03.575Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The abstract has line breaks in it which should be removed for IEEE single-paragraph format. Let me also check the other sections and create the paper.tex.\n\nActually, looking at it more carefully, the abstract in the tex file has natural line breaks but LaTeX will treat them as spaces. The issue is there might be blank lines between paragraphs. Let me check if there are any \\n\\n (double newlines) that would create paragraph breaks.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_6f1cc77ea69a4a08b36dd19d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check for blank lines in abstract (should be single paragraph)\ncat -A /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/abstract.tex | grep '^\\$\\|^$'","timeout":5}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":420,"output":257,"cacheRead":123264,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":123941,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775195157169}}
{"type":"message","id":"5e74a967","parentId":"c9129d13","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:46:03.588Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_6f1cc77ea69a4a08b36dd19d","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"$\n$\n$\n$\n$"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":9,"aggregated":"$\n$\n$\n$\n$","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775195163585}}
{"type":"message","id":"5059ff5f","parentId":"5e74a967","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:46:09.944Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There are multiple blank lines in the abstract, which would create multiple paragraphs. IEEE abstracts must be single paragraph. I need to fix this when creating paper.tex. Let me now read all the section files and assemble them into paper.tex.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Abstract has multiple paragraphs — needs to be merged into single paragraph. Let me now read all sections and assemble paper.tex."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_4ac19c6a25ea4c239a8f5fef","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3/introduction.tex"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":220,"output":166,"cacheRead":123648,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":124034,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775195163588}}
{"type":"message","id":"1aa8640b","parentId":"5059ff5f","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:46:09.949Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_4ac19c6a25ea4c239a8f5fef","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\\section{Introduction}\n\nRotating machinery, including critical components such as bearings, gears, and motors, serves as the foundational element of modern industrial infrastructures. These systems span a wide array of applications, from power generation facilities and manufacturing plants to aviation operations and petrochemical processing units \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. Operating under rigorous conditions---characterized by elevated rotational speeds, dynamic load variations, and harsh environmental influences---these components are prone to developing faults, including material wear, structural cracks, and dynamic imbalances. When such faults remain undetected, they can escalate rapidly into catastrophic system failures, incurring enormous economic repercussions estimated in the billions of dollars each year, alongside extensive unplanned downtime and profound safety risks to personnel and assets \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Real-world incidents poignantly illustrate this susceptibility. For example, the 2009 gearbox malfunctions at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm compromised 80 turbines, primarily due to progressive gear wear that resulted in more than 10\\% loss of overall capacity. Similarly, the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 experienced an uncontained engine failure in a Rolls-Royce Trent 900, which was later traced to initial bearing degradation. The 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 incident, involving fan blade detachment, was likewise rooted in bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}.\n\nEarly fault diagnosis methodologies predominantly depended on physics-based modeling coupled with classical signal processing techniques, including Fourier transforms for frequency-domain analysis and wavelet transforms for time-frequency localization. The integration of deep learning paradigms has markedly advanced this domain, with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit} achieving leading results on established benchmark datasets such as CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing}. These architectures autonomously derive multi-level hierarchical feature representations from raw vibration signals and other sensor data \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these strides, methods relying on a single modality often struggle to capture the full spectrum of complex fault patterns, particularly in scenarios involving fluctuating operational parameters, thereby necessitating the adoption of multimodal fusion strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n\nMultimodal data fusion has gained prominence as a potent methodology to augment the reliability and accuracy of fault diagnosis by exploiting synergistic information from diverse sensor types. Vibration signals, acquired through accelerometers, encapsulate the temporal evolution of mechanical disturbances; thermal imaging unveils anomalous heat patterns stemming from frictional losses or misalignment; and acoustic emission monitoring identifies nascent cracks through characteristic high-frequency emissions \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Empirical investigations reveal that advanced fusion techniques---employing attention-based mechanisms or graph neural networks---consistently deliver accuracy enhancements of 5\\% to 10\\% relative to unimodal approaches, with pronounced benefits observed under non-stationary conditions like varying speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. Nevertheless, practical deployment in industrial environments introduces substantial hurdles. Sensor data is frequently contaminated by noise arising from electromagnetic interference, mechanical vibrations, or ambient factors; moreover, partial occlusions, sensor malfunctions, or data transmission failures lead to missing modalities in as many as 50\\% of operational instances. Conventional fusion schemes, whether early concatenation or late decision-level integration, presuppose complete and clean data availability, rendering them vulnerable to misalignment errors exacerbated by noise \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n\nThe evolution toward multimodal large language models (MLLMs) introduces a sophisticated layer of capability, harnessing extensive vision-language pretraining to process and reason over images, spectrograms, and descriptive text. Prominent exemplars include LLaVA \\cite{liu2023llava,lu2024}, BLIP-2 \\cite{blip2}, Flamingo \\cite{flamingo}, and Qwen-VL \\cite{qwen}, which showcase exceptional zero-shot generalization on everyday natural images. In the specialized realm of industrial fault diagnosis, however, these models encounter pronounced limitations: artifacts prevalent in spectrograms derived from vibration data perplex visual encoders; thermal images, lacking structured semantic cues, incite erroneous hallucinations during fault localization; and rigorous evaluations on prognostics and health management (PHM) datasets document accuracy degradations of 15--20\\% in noisy regimes---for instance, LLaVA's bearing fault classification accuracy declining from 92\\% to 74\\% at 20 dB signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), alongside Qwen-VL's thermal anomaly detection falling from 88\\% to 70\\% in dusty operational contexts \\cite{hoang2025,kim2024,lu2024}.\n\nA salient research void in MLLMs for industrial applications lies in the robust handling of noisy or missing multimodal data streams. Although generative adversarial networks (GANs) \\cite{arjovsky2017wgan,wu2023} and synthetic minority over-sampling technique (SMOTE) derivatives adeptly tackle class imbalances, they inadequately address inter-modal inconsistencies or outright modality absences, often generating features that are misaligned and detrimental to subsequent fusion processes \\cite{wu2023,guo2023}. Standard imputation tactics---such as mean-value substitution or linear interpolation---overlook the intricate temporal-spatial dependencies in multimodal sensor signals, producing reconstructions that underperform amid varying operational regimes \\cite{guo2023}. Contemporary approaches are encumbered by five principal shortcomings: (1) inadequate enforcement of cross-modal consistency during synthetic data synthesis; (2) oversight of distinct noise profiles unique to each modality; (3) omission of uncertainty estimation within fusion mechanisms; (4) lack of external knowledge retrieval to inform imputation; and (5) deficient end-to-end optimization calibrated to authentic noise distributions \\cite{wu2023,guo2023,gal2016dropout}. Conventional attention modules in prevailing MLLMs exacerbate noise propagation by failing to modulate weights according to modal trustworthiness; furthermore, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)---proven effective in natural language processing \\cite{lewis2020rag}---has yet to be tailored for multimodal imputation in fault diagnosis contexts. Collectively, these deficiencies manifest as 20--50\\% performance deficits on authentic industrial datasets marred by noise and incompleteness, compounded by the dearth of standardized evaluation frameworks for degraded multimodal fault diagnosis \\cite{explainable2024,deployment2025}.\n\nThis work proffers four key contributions to bridge these gaps. First, we propose an adaptive cross-modal RAG imputation module that interrogates a vector database populated with historical pristine multimodal exemplars, thereby reconstructing absent or corrupted modalities using modality-specific vision-language prompts; this preserves essential temporal and semantic coherence across vibration spectrograms, thermal imagery, and acoustic waveforms. Second, an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism, grounded in evidential deep learning principles, dynamically calibrates modal reliabilities to suppress error propagation during fusion and elevate decision confidence amid partial observability. Third, an end-to-end training regimen employs reinforcement learning, wherein diagnostic policies are refined through rewards that prioritize both diagnostic precision and resilience to emulated industrial perturbations, including 20--50\\% noise augmentation. Fourth, thorough empirical validation across benchmark datasets (CWRU, Paderborn) and proprietary industrial corpora---incorporating simulated missing modality rates up to 50\\%---yields accuracy elevations of 12--18\\% over competing baselines, while upholding superior robustness.\n\nThe remainder of this paper is structured as follows. Section~\\ref{sec:background} provides a comprehensive review of related literature. Section~\\ref{sec:method} delineates the architecture and algorithms of the proposed RobustMLLM-Diag framework. Section~\\ref{sec:experiments} expounds upon the experimental setup, results, and ablation studies. Section~\\ref{sec:conclusion} summarizes key findings and outlines avenues for future research.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775195169946}}
{"type":"message","id":"9729c23d","parentId":"1aa8640b","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:46:17.658Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me continue reading the other sections to build the paper.tex. I'll need background, method, experiments, and conclusion. But this is going to be very long to read all sections. Let me take a more efficient approach - I'll create the paper.tex by including each section with \\input commands, or I'll concatenate them directly.\n\nActually, the best approach is to create paper.tex with the template structure and \\input{section_file} for each section. This way each section is a separate file and paper.tex is the main file that ties everything together. This is how the previous projects did it.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me read all remaining sections quickly and assemble paper.tex:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_e97921ece5054c8191ad64fa","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"SHARED=\"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/drafts/v3\"\nfor f in background method experiments conclusion; do\n  echo \"=== $f.tex first 3 lines ===\"\n  head -3 \"$SHARED/$f.tex\"\n  echo \"...\"\ndone","timeout":5}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":2001,"output":352,"cacheRead":123840,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":126193,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775195169950}}
{"type":"message","id":"1f288320","parentId":"9729c23d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:46:17.673Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_e97921ece5054c8191ad64fa","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"=== background.tex first 3 lines ===\n\\section{Theoretical Background}\n\nBuilding upon the multimodal challenges and gaps in noisy fault diagnosis discussed in Section~\\ref{sec:intro}, this section outlines the key theoretical foundations of our RobustMLLM-Diag framework, as shown in Fig.~\\ref{fig:overview} (Fig. 1) and Fig.~\\ref{fig:noise_patterns} (Fig. 2). We examine multimodal large language models (MLLMs), retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), uncertainty estimation, and reinforcement learning (RL) approaches for robustness. These elements establish the basis for adaptive imputation and fusion when dealing with noise and missing data.\n...\n=== method.tex first 3 lines ===\n\\section{Proposed Method}\n\\label{sec:method}\n\n...\n=== experiments.tex first 3 lines ===\n\\section{Experiments}\n\\label{sec:experiments}\n\n...\n=== conclusion.tex first 3 lines ===\n\\section{Conclusion}\n\\label{sec:conclusion}\n\n..."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":10,"aggregated":"=== background.tex first 3 lines ===\n\\section{Theoretical Background}\n\nBuilding upon the multimodal challenges and gaps in noisy fault diagnosis discussed in Section~\\ref{sec:intro}, this section outlines the key theoretical foundations of our RobustMLLM-Diag framework, as shown in Fig.~\\ref{fig:overview} (Fig. 1) and Fig.~\\ref{fig:noise_patterns} (Fig. 2). We examine multimodal large language models (MLLMs), retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), uncertainty estimation, and reinforcement learning (RL) approaches for robustness. These elements establish the basis for adaptive imputation and fusion when dealing with noise and missing data.\n...\n=== method.tex first 3 lines ===\n\\section{Proposed Method}\n\\label{sec:method}\n\n...\n=== experiments.tex first 3 lines ===\n\\section{Experiments}\n\\label{sec:experiments}\n\n...\n=== conclusion.tex first 3 lines ===\n\\section{Conclusion}\n\\label{sec:conclusion}\n\n...","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775195177669}}
{"type":"message","id":"05368af7","parentId":"1f288320","timestamp":"2026-04-03T05:46:46.593Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, I have the structure. Let me now create paper.tex. I'll use \\input{} commands to include each section file, plus the standard IEEE template preamble and formatting.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Now I'll assemble paper.tex with the IEEE template:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_79273fac175a43608e7514dc","name":"write","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/final/v1/paper.tex","content":"\\documentclass[lettersize,journal]{IEEEtran}\n\\usepackage{amsmath,amsfonts}\n\\usepackage{algorithmic}\n\\usepackage{algorithm}\n\\usepackage{array}\n\\usepackage[caption=false,font=normalsize,labelfont=sf,textfont=sf]{subfig}\n\\usepackage{textcomp}\n\\usepackage{stfloats}\n\\usepackage{url}\n\\usepackage{verbatim}\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\usepackage{cite}\n\\hyphenation{op-tical net-works semi-conduc-tor IEEE-Xplore}\n\n\\begin{document}\n\n\\title{RobustMLLM-Diag: Adaptive Cross-Modal Imputation and Fusion\\\\in Multimodal Large Language Models\\\\for Noisy Fault Diagnosis}\n\n\\author{Anonymous Authors}\n\n\\maketitle\n\n\\begin{abstract}\nIndustrial fault diagnosis is challenged by noisy and incomplete multimodal data, encompassing vibration signals, thermal images, acoustic emissions, and spectra. Typically, 20--50\\% of these modalities are missing or corrupted owing to sensor failures or environmental noise. Prevailing Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) depend on inflexible fusion strategies ill-equipped to handle input uncertainties, which erodes diagnostic precision. RobustMLLM-Diag introduces an MLLM framework tailored for resilient fault diagnosis. The approach incorporates Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) for adaptive cross-modal imputation that reconstructs missing data, coupled with an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism to facilitate robust feature fusion. Among its key features are Bayesian dropout for uncertainty quantification, dynamic weighting of modalities according to their reliability, and reinforcement learning to enhance robustness against varying noise levels. Experiments conducted on benchmark datasets show that RobustMLLM-Diag exceeds existing methods by more than 15\\% in accuracy under conditions of 50\\% noise corruption and modality dropout. Such performance enables dependable deployment in safety-critical rotating machinery, markedly progressing prognostics and health management in industrial contexts.\n\\end{abstract}\n\n\\begin{IEEEkeywords}\nMultimodal large language model, fault diagnosis, cross-modal imputation, uncertainty-aware fusion, Bayesian dropout, dynamic modality weighting, reinforcement learning, prognostics and health management\n\\end{IEEEkeywords}\n\n\\section{Introduction}\n\\label{sec:intro}\n\nRotating machinery, including critical components such as bearings, gears, and motors, serves as the foundational element of modern industrial infrastructures. These systems span a wide array of applications, from power generation facilities and manufacturing plants to aviation operations and petrochemical processing units \\cite{wen2017,li2021,he2016resnet}. Operating under rigorous conditions---characterized by elevated rotational speeds, dynamic load variations, and harsh environmental influences---these components are prone to developing faults, including material wear, structural cracks, and dynamic imbalances. When such faults remain undetected, they can escalate rapidly into catastrophic system failures, incurring enormous economic repercussions estimated in the billions of dollars each year, alongside extensive unplanned downtime and profound safety risks to personnel and assets \\cite{li2023,wen2024,ieee1888}. Real-world incidents poignantly illustrate this susceptibility. For example, the 2009 gearbox malfunctions at Denmark's Horns Rev 1 offshore wind farm compromised 80 turbines, primarily due to progressive gear wear that resulted in more than 10\\% loss of overall capacity. Similarly, the 2010 Qantas Flight 32 experienced an uncontained engine failure in a Rolls-Royce Trent 900, which was later traced to initial bearing degradation. The 2018 Southwest Airlines Flight 1380 incident, involving fan blade detachment, was likewise rooted in bearing fatigue \\cite{li2023,wen2024}.\n\nEarly fault diagnosis methodologies predominantly depended on physics-based modeling coupled with classical signal processing techniques, including Fourier transforms for frequency-domain analysis and wavelet transforms for time-frequency localization. The integration of deep learning paradigms has markedly advanced this domain, with convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \\cite{wen2017cnn} and vision transformers (ViTs) \\cite{dosovitskiy2021vit} achieving leading results on established benchmark datasets such as CWRU \\cite{cwrudataset,smith2004} and Paderborn \\cite{paderborn2014,pubearing}. These architectures autonomously derive multi-level hierarchical feature representations from raw vibration signals and other sensor data \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,li2021transformer}. Despite these strides, methods relying on a single modality often struggle to capture the full spectrum of complex fault patterns, particularly in scenarios involving fluctuating operational parameters, thereby necessitating the adoption of multimodal fusion strategies \\cite{li2023}.\n\nMultimodal data fusion has gained prominence as a potent methodology to augment the reliability and accuracy of fault diagnosis by exploiting synergistic information from diverse sensor types. Vibration signals, acquired through accelerometers, encapsulate the temporal evolution of mechanical disturbances; thermal imaging unveils anomalous heat patterns stemming from frictional losses or misalignment; and acoustic emission monitoring identifies nascent cracks through characteristic high-frequency emissions \\cite{chen2022,zhang2024,earlyfusion}. Empirical investigations reveal that advanced fusion techniques---employing attention-based mechanisms or graph neural networks---consistently deliver accuracy enhancements of 5\\% to 10\\% relative to unimodal approaches, with pronounced benefits observed under non-stationary conditions like varying speeds and loads \\cite{jia2023,gao2025}. Nevertheless, practical deployment in industrial environments introduces substantial hurdles. Sensor data is frequently contaminated by noise arising from electromagnetic interference, mechanical vibrations, or ambient factors; moreover, partial occlusions, sensor malfunctions, or data transmission failures lead to missing modalities in as many as 50\\% of operational instances. Conventional fusion schemes, whether early concatenation or late decision-level integration, presuppose complete and clean data availability, rendering them vulnerable to misalignment errors exacerbated by noise \\cite{liu2023,sun2025,earlyfusion}.\n\nThe evolution toward multimodal large language models (MLLMs) introduces a sophisticated layer of capability, harnessing extensive vision-language pretraining to process and reason over images, spectrograms, and descriptive text. Prominent exemplars include LLaVA \\cite{liu2023llava,lu2024}, BLIP-2 \\cite{blip2}, Flamingo \\cite{flamingo}, and Qwen-VL \\cite{qwen}, which showcase exceptional zero-shot generalization on everyday natural images. In the specialized realm of industrial fault diagnosis, however, these models encounter pronounced limitations: artifacts prevalent in spectrograms derived from vibration data perplex visual encoders; thermal images, lacking structured semantic cues, incite erroneous hallucinations during fault localization; and rigorous evaluations on prognostics and health management (PHM) datasets document accuracy degradations of 15--20\\% in noisy regimes---for instance, LLaVA's bearing fault classification accuracy declining from 92\\% to 74\\% at 20 dB signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), alongside Qwen-VL's thermal anomaly detection falling from 88\\% to 70\\% in dusty operational contexts \\cite{hoang2025,kim2024,lu2024}.\n\nA salient research void in MLLMs for industrial applications lies in the robust handling of noisy or missing multimodal data streams. Although generative adversarial networks (GANs) \\cite{arjovsky2017wgan,wu2023} and synthetic minority over-sampling technique (SMOTE) derivatives adeptly tackle class imbalances, they inadequately address inter-modal inconsistencies or outright modality absences, often generating features that are misaligned and detrimental to subsequent fusion processes \\cite{wu2023,guo2023}. Standard imputation tactics---such as mean-value substitution or linear interpolation---overlook the intricate temporal-spatial dependencies in multimodal sensor signals, producing reconstructions that underperform amid varying operational regimes \\cite{guo2023}. Contemporary approaches are encumbered by five principal shortcomings: (1) inadequate enforcement of cross-modal consistency during synthetic data synthesis; (2) oversight of distinct noise profiles unique to each modality; (3) omission of uncertainty estimation within fusion mechanisms; (4) lack of external knowledge retrieval to inform imputation; and (5) deficient end-to-end optimization calibrated to authentic noise distributions \\cite{wu2023,guo2023,gal2016dropout}. Conventional attention modules in prevailing MLLMs exacerbate noise propagation by failing to modulate weights according to modal trustworthiness; furthermore, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)---proven effective in natural language processing \\cite{lewis2020rag}---has yet to be tailored for multimodal imputation in fault diagnosis contexts. Collectively, these deficiencies manifest as 20--50\\% performance deficits on authentic industrial datasets marred by noise and incompleteness, compounded by the dearth of standardized evaluation frameworks for degraded multimodal fault diagnosis \\cite{explainable2024,deployment2025}.\n\nThis work proffers four key contributions to bridge these gaps. First, we propose an adaptive cross-modal RAG imputation module that interrogates a vector database populated with historical pristine multimodal exemplars, thereby reconstructing absent or corrupted modalities using modality-specific vision-language prompts; this preserves essential temporal and semantic coherence across vibration spectrograms, thermal imagery, and acoustic waveforms. Second, an uncertainty-aware attention mechanism, grounded in evidential deep learning principles, dynamically calibrates modal reliabilities to suppress error propagation during fusion and elevate decision confidence amid partial observability. Third, an end-to-end training regimen employs reinforcement learning, wherein diagnostic policies are refined through rewards that prioritize both diagnostic precision and resilience to emulated industrial perturbations, including 20--50\\% noise augmentation. Fourth, thorough empirical validation across benchmark datasets (CWRU, Paderborn) and proprietary industrial corpora---incorporating simulated missing modality rates up to 50\\%---yields accuracy elevations of 12--18\\% over competing baselines, while upholding superior robustness.\n\nThe remainder of this paper is structured as follows. Section~\\ref{sec:background} provides a comprehensive review of related literature. Section~\\ref{sec:method} delineates the architecture and algorithms of the proposed RobustMLLM-Diag framework. Section~\\ref{sec:experiments} expounds upon the experimental setup, results, and ablation studies. Section~\\ref{sec:conclusion} summarizes key findings and outlines avenues for future research.\n\n\\input{background}\n\\input{method}\n\\input{experiments}\n\\input{conclusion}\n\n\\bibliographystyle{plain}\n\\bibliography{references}\n\n\\end{document}\n"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"xiaomi/mimo-v2-pro","usage":{"input":478,"output":2507,"cacheRead":125824,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":128809,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775195177673}}
