{"type":"message","id":"f9ce4844","parentId":"0f89954d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T06:07:25.057Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_d31ed53b2341491095b38916","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-9/final/v1/method.tex."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  74 \n  75 Reconstruction fidelity is quantified using the 1-Wasserstein distance (optimal transport cost) between $\\hat{x}_i$ and the top retrieved $x_i^{j^*}$:\n  76 \\begin{equation}\n  77 W_1(\\hat{x}_i, x_i^{j^*}) = \\inf_{\\gamma \\in \\Pi(\\mathbb{P}_{\\hat{x}_i}, \\mathbb{P}_{x_i^{j^*}})} \\int \\|z - z'\\| \\, d\\gamma(z, z'),\n- 78 \\label{eq:wasserstein}\n+ 78 \\label{eq:wasserstein2}\n  79 \\end{equation}\n  80 approximated efficiently with Sinkhorn-Knopp iterations (20 iterations, $\\epsilon=0.01$). If $W_1 < \\delta=0.15$ (empirically tuned), $\\hat{x}_i$ is encoded to $\\hat{h}_i, \\hat{u}_i$; else, modality $i$ is masked.\n  81 \n  82 This cross-modal RAG outperforms naive imputation (e.g., zero-filling, mean) by 12--18\\% in accuracy under 40\\% random modality dropout, surpassing domain-specific diffusion models. Compared to vanilla RAG~\\cite{lewis2020retrieval}, our CLIP-based retrieval achieves 25\\% higher recall@5 across heterogeneous modalities, as ablated on simulated PU data with thermal occlusion.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":78},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775196445052}}
